 \"New Media\", ''University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign'']\n* {{cite book|first=J\u00f6rn Peter |last=Hiekel|year=2009|title=Vernetzungen: Neue Musik im Spannungsfeld von Wissenschaft und Technik|publisher=Institut f\u00fcr Neue Musik und Musikerziehung Darmstadt|oclc=320198124}} \n* Bailey, Chris & Hazel Gardiner. (2010). Revisualizing Visual Culture. Surrey, UK: Ashgate Publishing.\n* Jana, Reena and Mark Tribe. (2009). New Media Art. New York: Taschen.\n* Dale Hudson and Patricia R. Zimmermann. (2009). \u201cTaking Things Apart: Migratory Archives, Locative Media, and Micropublics.\u201d ''Afterimage'' vol. 36 no. 4 (January/February), pp.&nbsp;14\u201319.\n* [http://rhizome.org/editorial/2008/dec/3/thoughts-on-quotnew-media-artists-vs- artists-with-/ Moss, Ceci. (2008). Thoughts on \u201cNew Media Artists v. Artists with Computers\u201d. ''Rhizome'']{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://hyperallergic.com/79749/whither-art-david-joselits-digital-art-problem/ Nechvatal, Joseph. (2013). Whither Art? David Joselit's Digital Art Problem. \"Hyperallergic: Sensitive to Art & its Discontents.\"]\n* Joselit, David. (2012). ''After Art''. Princeton: Princeton University Press. {{ISBN|9780691150444}}.\n* Guertin, C. (2012). D''igital prohibition: Piracy and authorship in new media art''. London: Continuum International Pub. Group. {{ISBN|9781441106100}}.\n* Catrical\u00e0, Valentino (2013). \"Come l\u2019avanguardia invent\u00f2 il futuro. L\u2019Optofono di Raoul Hausman, la 'visione elettromeccanica' di Lissitzky e le forme dell\u2019energia\", in \"Imago. Rivista di studi sul cinema e i media\", n. 7-8. (pp.&nbsp;277\u2013294). {{ISSN|2038-5536}} [https://www.academia.edu/4941377/Come_l_avanguardia_invent%C3%B2_il_futuro._L_Optofono_di_Raoul_Hausman_la_visione_elettromeccanica_di_Lissitzky_e_le_forme_dell_energia_How_the_avant-garde_invented_the_future._The_Raoul_Hausmann_s_Optophone_the_Lissitzky_s_electromecchanic_vision_and_the_shapes_of_energies]\n* Dale Hudson and Patricia R. Zimmermann. (2015). ''[http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/thinking-through-digital-media-dale-hudson/?K=9781137433626 Thinking Through Digital Media Transnational Environments and Locative Places].'' New York: Palgrave Macmillan. {{ISBN|978-1137433626}} '''[https://www.thinkingthroughdigitalmedia.com companion website with links to projects]'''\n*Janez Strehovec (2016). ''Text as Ride''. Electronic Literature and New Media Art. Morgentown: West Virginia University Press (''Computing Literature'' book series)-\n\n{{Western art movements}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:New media art| New media art]]\n[[Category:Media technology]]\n[[Category:Visual arts genres]]\n[[Category:New media]]\n", "name_user": "2001:b07:a5a:22dd:7915:7e2:79e7:eab2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_media_art"}
{"title_page": "Pop music", "text_new": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-1950s deriving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = The Righteous Brothers \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s, improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s) and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a specific music genre|popular music in general|Popular music|other uses|Pop music (disambiguation)}}\n{{Redirect|Pop song|other uses|Pop Song (disambiguation){{!}}Pop Song}}\n{{short description|Genre of popular music which originated in its modern form in the late-1950s deriving from rock and roll}}\n{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Pop\n| color = pink\n| bgcolor = #87CEEB\n| stylistic_origins = \n* [[Traditional pop music|Traditional pop]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/subgenre/traditional-pop-ma0000002961/artists  Traditional Pop, ''Allmusic.com''].  Retrieved 25 August 2016</ref>\n* [[rock and roll]]<ref name=Grove/>\n* [[Contemporary folk music|folk]]<ref name=pc1/>\n| cultural_origins = Mid-1950s,<ref name=Firth2001/> United States and United Kingdom\n| image = \n| caption = mj\n| derivatives = * [[Disco]]\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n| instruments = \n| subgenrelist = List of pop music genres\n| subgenres = * [[Art pop]]\n* [[Brill Building (genre)|Brill Building]]\n* [[bubblegum pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[experimental pop]]\n* [[hypnagogic pop]]\n* [[new wave]]\n* [[operatic pop]]\n* [[orchestral pop]]\n* [[progressive pop]]\n* [[sophisti-pop]]\n* [[space age pop]]\n* [[sunshine pop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[teen pop]]\n* pop-ballad<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/pop-ballad|title=Pop ballad &#124; sentimental song|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/3814513|title=Genre and the Ballad|author=Seeger, Judith|year=1994|journal=Journal of Folklore Research|volume=31|issue=1/3|pages=151\u2013176|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n| fusiongenres = * [[Baroque pop]]\n* [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]]\n* [[country pop]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[folk-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[jangle pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[noise pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[psychedelic pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[reggae fusion]]\n* [[smooth jazz]]\n* [[smooth soul]]\n| regional_scenes = * [[C-pop|China]]\n* [[Indian pop|India]]\n* [[Indo pop|Indonesia]]\n* [[Cantopop|Hong Kong]]\n* [[Italian popular music#Contemporary Music|Italy]]\n* [[J-pop|Japan]]\n* [[K-pop|Korea]]\n* [[Malaysian pop|Malaysia]]\n* [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]]\n* [[Moroccan pop|Morocco]]\n* [[Pakistani pop music|Pakistan]]\n* [[P-pop|Philippines]]\n* [[Russian pop|Russia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Scandinavia]]\n* [[Swedish pop music|Sweden]]\n* [[Taiwanese pop|Taiwan]]\n* [[Thai pop music|Thailand]]\n* [[Turkish pop music|Turkey]]\n* [[British pop music|United Kingdom]]\n* [[American pop|United States]]\n* [[V-pop|Vietnam]]\n* [[Europop|Western Europe]]\n| local_scenes = \n| other_topics = * [[Avant-pop]]\n* [[pop music automation]]\n* [[poptimism]]\n* [[rock music]]\n| current_year = no\n}}\n'''Pop music''' is a genre of [[popular music]] that originated in its modern forms in the [[United States|US]] and the [[United Kingdom|UK]] during the mid-1950s.<ref name=Firth2001/> The terms \"popular music\" and \"pop music\" are often used interchangeably, although the former describes all music that is popular and includes many diverse styles. \"Pop\" and \"[[Rock music|rock]]\" were roughly synonymous terms until the late 1960s, when they became quite separated from each other.\n\nAlthough much of the music that appears on [[record chart]]s is seen as pop music, the genre is distinguished from chart music. Pop music often borrows elements from other styles such as [[urban contemporary|urban]], [[dance music|dance]], [[rock music|rock]], [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]], and [[country music|country]]; nevertheless, there are many key elements that define pop music. Identifying factors usually include short to medium-length songs written in a basic format (often the [[verse\u2013chorus form|verse-chorus structure]]), as well as common use of repeated choruses, melodic tunes and [[hook (music)|hooks]].\n\n==Definitions and etymology{{anchor|Etymology}}==\n[[File:The Beatles in America.JPG|thumb|left|The 1960s [[British Invasion]] marked a period when the US charts were inundated with British acts such as [[the Beatles]] (pictured 1964).]]\n\nDavid Hatch and Stephen Millward define pop music as \"a body of music which is distinguishable from popular, jazz, and folk musics\".<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1987), {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 1.</ref>\nAccording to [[Pete Seeger]], pop music is \"professional music which draws upon both folk music and fine arts music\".<ref name=pc1>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19745/m1/ |title=Show 1 \u2013 Play A Simple Melody: Pete Seeger on the origins of pop music}}</ref>\nAlthough pop music is seen as just the [[record chart|singles charts]], it is not the sum of all chart music. The music charts contain songs from a variety of sources, including [[classical music|classical]], [[jazz]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[novelty song]]s. As a genre, pop music is seen to exist and develop separately.<ref>R. Serge Denisoff and William L. Schurk, ''Tarnished Gold: the Record Industry Revisited'' (New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers, 3rd edn., 1986), {{ISBN|0-88738-618-0}}, pp. 2\u20133.</ref> Therefore, the term \"pop music\" may be used to describe a distinct genre, designed to appeal to all, often characterized as \"instant singles-based music aimed at teenagers\" in contrast to rock music as \"album-based music for adults\".<ref name=Firth2001/>{{refn|Musicologist Allan Moore surmises that the term \"pop music\" itself may have been popularized by [[Pop art]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan F.|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}</ref>}}\n\nPop music continuously evolves along with the term's definition. According to music writer Bill Lamb, popular music is defined as \"the music since industrialization in the 1800s that is most in line with the tastes and interests of the urban middle class.\"<ref name=\"What Is Pop Music\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/what-is-pop-music-3246980|title=What Is Pop Music?|access-date=|last = Lamb |first =Bill|website = ThoughtCo.|date = 29 September 2018 }}</ref> The term \"pop song\" was first used in 1926, in the sense of a piece of music \"having popular appeal\".<ref name=OED>J. Simpson and E. Weiner, ''Oxford English Dictionary''(Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1989). {{ISBN|0-19-861186-2}}, cf. pop.</ref> Hatch and Millward indicate that many events in the history of recording in the 1920s can be seen as the birth of the modern pop music industry, including in [[country music|country]], [[blues]], and [[hillbilly music]].<ref>D. Hatch and S. Millward, ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}, p. 49.</ref>\n\n[[File: Rolling stones - 11 luglio 2006 - san siro.jpg|thumb|right|''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that the term \"pop\" refers to music performed by such artists as  [[the Rolling Stones]] (pictured here in a 2006 performance).]]\n\nAccording to the website of ''[[The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians]]'', the term \"pop music\" \"originated in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in the mid-1950s as a description for [[rock and roll]] and the new youth music styles that it influenced\".<ref name=Grove>R. Middleton, et al., [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_gmo \"Pop\"], ''Grove music online'', retrieved 14 March 2010. {{Subscription required}}</ref> ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'' states that while pop's \"earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience [...] since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus[ic], usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[ABBA]], etc.\"<ref>\"Pop\", [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/public/book/omo_t237 ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music''], retrieved 9 March 2010.{{Subscription required}}</ref> ''Grove Music Online'' also states that \"[...] in the early 1960s, [the term] 'pop music' competed terminologically with [[beat music]] [in England], while in the US its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of 'rock and roll'\".<ref name=Grove/>\n\nFrom about 1967, the term \u201cpop music\u201d was increasingly used in opposition to the term [[rock music]], a division that gave generic significance to both terms.<ref name=Gloag983>Kenneth Gloag in ''The Oxford Companion to Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-19-866212-2}}, p. 983.</ref> While rock aspired to [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]] and an expansion of the possibilities of popular music,<ref name=Gloag983/> pop was more commercial, ephemeral, and accessible.<ref name=Warner2003>T. Warner, ''Pop Music: Technology and Creativity: Trevor Horn and the Digital Revolution'' (Aldershot: Ashgate, 2003), {{ISBN|0-7546-3132-X}}, pp.&nbsp;3\u20134.</ref> According to British musicologist [[Simon Frith]], pop music is produced \"as a matter of [[business|enterprise]] not art\", and is \"designed to appeal to everyone\" but \"doesn't come from any particular place or mark off any particular taste\". Frith adds that it is \"not driven by any significant ambition except profit and commercial reward [...] and, in musical terms, it is essentially conservative\". It is, \"provided from on high (by record companies, radio programmers, and concert promoters) rather than being made from below&nbsp;... Pop is not a [[DIY|do-it-yourself]] music but is professionally produced and packaged\".<ref name=\"Firth2001\"/> {{clear}}\n\n==Characteristics==\n[[File:Elvis_Presley_-_TV_Radio_Mirror,_March_1957_01.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Elvis Presley]]]]\n\n{{listen\n | filename    = Righteous Brothers - You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'.ogg\n | title       = The Righteous Brothers \u2013 \"You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin'\" (1965)\n | pos         = right\n | description ={{As of|2011}}, \"[[You've Lost That Lovin' Feelin']]\" ranks as the most frequently played song in US radio history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15186967 |title=Van's Brown Eyed Girl hits the 10 million mark in US|date=5 October 2011 |work=BBC }}</ref> It is described by music writers [[Nick Logan]] and [[Bob Woffinden]] as \"the ultimate pop record\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Great Popular Song Recordings, Volume 2|author=Steve Sullivan|pages=101\u2013103 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |year=2013 |isbn= 978-0-8108-8296-6 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAccording to Frith, characteristics of pop music include an aim of appealing to a general audience, rather than to a particular sub-culture or ideology, and an emphasis on craftsmanship rather than formal \"artistic\" qualities.<ref name=Firth2001/> Music scholar Timothy Warner said it typically has an emphasis on recording, production, and technology, rather than live performance; a tendency to reflect existing trends rather than [[progressive music|progressive developments]]; and aims to encourage dancing or uses dance-oriented rhythms.<ref name=Warner2003/>\n\nThe main medium of pop music is the song, often between two and a half and three and a half minutes in length, generally marked by a consistent and noticeable [[rhythm|rhythmic element]], a mainstream style and a simple traditional [[song structure (popular music)|structure]].<ref>W. Everett, ''Expression in Pop-rock Music: A Collection of Critical and Analytical Essays'' (London: Taylor & Francis, 2000), p. 272.</ref> Common variants include the verse-chorus form and the [[thirty-two-bar form]], with a focus on [[melody|melodies]] and catchy [[hook (music)|hooks]], and a [[refrain|chorus]] that contrasts melodically, rhythmically and [[harmony|harmonically]] with the [[Verse (music)|verse]].<ref>J. Shepherd, ''Continuum Encyclopedia of Popular Music of the World: Performance and production'' (Continuum, 2003), p. 508.</ref> The beat and the melodies tend to be simple, with limited harmonic accompaniment.<ref>V. Kramarz, ''The Pop Formulas: Harmonic Tools of the Hit Makers'' (Mel Bay Publications, 2007), p. 61.</ref> The lyrics of modern pop songs typically focus on simple themes&nbsp;\u2013 often love and romantic relationships&nbsp;\u2013 although there are notable exceptions.<ref name=Firth2001/>\n\n[[Harmony (music)|Harmony]] and [[chord progression]]s in pop music are often \"that of [[Classical music|classical]] European [[tonality]], only more simple-minded.\"<ref>Winkler, Peter (1978). \"Toward a theory of pop harmony\", ''In Theory Only'', 4, pp.&nbsp;3\u201326.</ref> Clich\u00e9s include the [[close and open harmony|barbershop quartet-style harmony]] (i.e. ii \u2013 V \u2013 I) and [[blues scale]]-influenced harmony.<ref>Sargeant, p. 198. cited in Winkler (1978), p. 4.</ref> There was a lessening of the influence of traditional views of the [[circle of fifths]] between the mid-1950s and the late 1970s, including less predominance for the [[dominant (music)|dominant]] [[diatonic function|function]].<ref>Winkler (1978), p. 22.</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Development and influence==\n\n===Technology and media===\n\n{{multiple image\n| total_width = 230\n| align = right\n| image1 = Michael Jackson in 1988.jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Madonna, Rotterdam, 26-8-1987.jpg\n| width2 = \n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = [[Michael Jackson]] (left) and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] (right), known respectively as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King and Queen of Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=April 17, 2013|title=Madonna Pop Art}}</ref>\n| direction = \n}}\n\nIn the 1940s improved [[microphone]] design allowed a more intimate singing style and ten or twenty years later, inexpensive and more durable 45 rpm records for singles \"revolutionized the manner in which pop has been disseminated\", which helped to move pop music to \"a record/radio/film star system\".<ref name=Buckley>D. Buckley, \"Pop\" \"II. Implications of technology\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 15 March 2010.</ref> Another technological change was the widespread availability of television in the 1950s; with televised performances, \"pop stars had to have a visual presence\".<ref name=Buckley/> In the 1960s, the introduction of inexpensive, portable [[transistor radio]]s meant that teenagers in the developed world could listen to music outside of the home.<ref name=Buckley/> By the early 1980s, the promotion of pop music had been greatly affected by the rise of music television channels like [[MTV]], which \"favoured those artists such as [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] who had a strong visual appeal\".<ref name=Buckley/>\n\n[[Multi-track recording]] (from the 1960s); and [[sampling (music)|digital sampling]] (from the 1980s) have also been utilized as methods for the creation and elaboration of pop music.<ref name=Firth2001/> During the mid-1960s, pop music made repeated forays into new sounds, styles, and techniques that inspired public discourse among its listeners. The word \"progressive\" was frequently used, and it was thought that every song and single was to be a \"progression\" from the last.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2|page=162}}</ref> [[Music journalism|Music critic]] [[Simon Reynolds]] writes that beginning with 1967, a divide would exist between \"progressive\" pop and \"mass/chart\" pop, a separation which was \"also, broadly, one between boys and girls, middle-class and working-class.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath|page=398}}</ref>\n\nThe latter half of the 20th-century included a large-scale trend in American culture in which the boundaries between art and pop music were increasingly blurred.<ref>{{cite book|pp=317, 1233|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}</ref> Between 1950 and 1970, there was a debate of pop versus art.<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\"/> Since then, certain music publications have embraced the music's legitimacy, a trend referred to as \"[[poptimism]]\".<ref name=\"PMLoss2015\">{{cite web|last1=Loss|first1=Robert|title=No Apologies: A Critique of the Rockist v. Poptimist Paradigm|url=http://www.popmatters.com/column/196122-no-apologies-a-critique-of-the-rockist-v.-poptimist-paradigm/|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Stylistic evolution===\n[[File:Katy_Perry_2011.jpg|thumb|left|[[Katy Perry]]'s characteristic spinning peppermint swirl dress which she wore during the California Dreams tour|alt=]]\n\nThroughout its development, pop music has absorbed influences from other genres of popular music. Early pop music drew on the [[sentimental ballad]] for its form, gained its use of vocal harmonies from [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[soul music]], instrumentation from [[jazz]] and [[rock music]], orchestration from [[classical music]], tempo from [[dance music]], backing from [[electronic music]], rhythmic elements from [[hip-hop music]], and spoken passages from [[rap music|rap]].<ref name=Firth2001>S. Frith, W. Straw, and J. Street, eds, ''[[Cambridge Companions to Music|The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp.&nbsp;95\u2013105.</ref>{{verification needed|date=February 2017}} In 2016, a ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' study that examined over 464,000 recordings of popular music recorded between 1955 and 2010 found that since the 1960s, pop music had found less variety in pitch progressions, grown average loudness levels,<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/srep00521|pmid=22837813|pmc=3405292|title=Measuring the Evolution of Contemporary Western Popular Music|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=2|pages=521|year=2012|last1=Serr\u00e0|first1=Joan|last2=Corral|first2=\u00c1lvaro|last3=Bogu\u00f1\u00e1|first3=Mari\u00e1n|last4=Haro|first4=Mart\u00edn|last5=Arcos|first5=Josep Ll.}}</ref> less diverse instrumentation and recording techniques, and less timbral variety.<ref name=\"Matson\"/> ''[[Scientific American]]''{{'}}s John Matson reported that this \"seems to support the popular anecdotal observation that pop music of yore was \"better\", or at least more varied, than today's top-40 stuff\". However, he also noted that the study may not have been entirely representative of pop in each generation.<ref name=\"Matson\">[http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/is-pop-music-evolving-or-is-it-just-getting-louder/ John Matson, \"Is Pop Music Evolving, or Is It Just Getting Louder?\", ''Scientific American'', 26 July 2012]. Retrieved 30 March 2016</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, the majority of mainstream pop music fell in two categories: guitar, drum and bass groups or singers backed by a traditional orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|title=Making Arrangements\u2014A Rough Guide To Song Construction & Arrangement, Part 1 |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |work=Sound on Sound |accessdate=8 May 2014 |date=October 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508082609/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/1997_articles/oct97/arranging1.html |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> Since early in the decade, it was common for pop producers, songwriters, and engineers to freely experiment with musical form, [[orchestration]], [[reverberation|unnatural reverb]], and other sound effects. Some of the best known examples are [[Phil Spector]]'s [[Wall of Sound]] and [[Joe Meek]]'s use of homemade electronic sound effects for acts like [[the Tornados]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Blake|first=Andrew|editor-last1=Cook|editor-first1=Nicholas|editor-last2=Clarke|editor-first2=Eric|editor-last3=Leech-Wilkinson|editor-first3=Daniel|title=The Cambridge Companion to Recorded Music|chapter=Recording practices and the role of the producer|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb0hAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82796-6|page=45}}</ref> At the same time, pop music on radio and in both American and British film moved away from refined [[Tin Pan Alley]] to more eccentric songwriting and incorporated reverb-drenched rock guitar, symphonic strings, and horns played by groups of properly arranged and rehearsed studio musicians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Pareles|date=October 31, 2008|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/arts/music/01pupp.html?_r=0|title=Orchestral Pop, the Way It Was (More or Less)|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 4, 2013}}</ref>  A 2019 study held by [[New York University]] in which 643 participants had to rank how familiar a pop song is to them, songs from the 1960s turned out to be the most memorable, significantly more than songs from recent years 2000 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smoothradio.com/news/music/best-decade-pop-music/|title=The greatest decade for pop music has been revealed (according to science)|website=Smooth|language=en|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[progressive pop]] of the late 1960s, performers were typically unable to decide on the artistic content of their music.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7|page=217}}</ref> Assisted by the mid-1960s economic boom, record labels began investing in artists, giving them the freedom to experiment, and offering them limited control over their content and marketing.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} This situation declined after the late 1970s and would not reemerge until the rise of [[Internet]] stars.{{sfn|Moore|2016|p=202}} [[Indie pop]], which developed in the late 1970s, marked another departure from the glamour of contemporary pop music, with guitar bands formed on the then-novel premise that one could record and release their own music without having to procure a [[record contract]] from a major label.<ref>{{Citation|title=Twee as Fuck: The Story of Indie Pop |first=Nitsuh |last=Abebe |work=Pitchfork Media |date=24 October 2005 |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wjlLnVho?url=http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6176-twee-as-fuck/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Latin pop]] rose in popularity in the [[United States]] during the 1950s with early rock and roll success [[Ritchie Valens]], though it truly rose to prominence during the 1970s and 1980s with the likes of [[Los Lobos]].<ref name=\"Portwood Portwood 2019\">{{cite web | last=Portwood | first=Jerry | last2=Portwood | first2=Jerry | title=Ritchie Valens Musical in the Works From Los Lobos' Louie Perez and David Hidalgo | website=Rolling Stone | date=December 12, 2019 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/ritchie-valens-musical-los-lobos-925326/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> With later [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] seeing success within pop music charts, 1990s pop successes stayed popular in both their original genres and in broader pop music. Artists like [[Selena]] saw large-scale pop music presence, and crossover appeal with fans of [[Tejano music]] trailblazers like [[Lydia Mendoza]]; likewise in other genres like [[Lorenzo Antonio]] and [[Sparx (US band)|Sparx]], who are recognized throughout [[Latin America]] as well as within their [[New Mexico music]] repertoire of [[Al Hurricane]] and [[Antonia Apodaca]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Aldama | first=A.J. | last2=Sandoval | first2=C. | last3=Garc\u00eda | first3=P.J. | title=Performing the US Latina and Latino Borderlands | publisher=Indiana University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-253-00295-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7KXaqig1YwC&pg=PA224 | access-date=February 14, 2020 | page=224}}</ref> Musicians like [[Shakira]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Selena Gomez]], and [[Demi Lovato]] seen lasting mass-appeal within pop music circles. Latin pop hit singles, like \u201c[[Macarena]]\u201d by [[Los del R\u00edo]] and \u201c[[Despacito]]\u201d by [[Luis Fonsi]] have seen record-breaking success on worldwide pop music charts.<ref name=\"Villafa\u00f1e 2017\">{{cite web | last=Villafa\u00f1e | first=Veronica | title=Still No.1, Record-Breaking 'Despacito' Ties 'Macarena' Streak On Hot 100, But Is Snubbed By MTV | website=Forbes | date=August 14, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/veronicavillafane/2017/08/14/still-no-1-record-breaking-despacito-ties-macarena-streak-on-hot-100-but-is-snubbed-by-mtv/ | access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1980s are commonly remembered for an increase in the use of [[digital recording]], associated with the usage of [[synthesizer]]s, with [[synth-pop]] music and other [[electronic music|electronic]] genres featuring non-traditional instruments increasing in popularity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/29/arts/rap-music-brash-and-swaggering-enters-mainstream.html | work=The New York Times | first=Glenn | last=Collins | title=Rap Music, Brash And Swaggering, Enters Mainstream | date=1988-08-29}}</ref> By 2014, pop music worldwide had been permeated by [[electronic dance music]].<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> In 2018, researchers at the [[University of California, Irvine]], concluded that pop music has become 'sadder' since the 1980s. The elements of [[happiness]] and brightness have eventually been replaced with the electronic beats making the pop music more 'sad yet danceable'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/05/16/sadness-in-pop-music-study|title=New study finds pop music has gotten extremely depressing but also more fun to dance to|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===International spread===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = The story of pop music is largely the story of the intertwining pop culture of the United States and the United Kingdom in the postwar era.\n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 [[Bob Stanley (musician)|Bob Stanley]]<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2014|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/bn2014-07.php|title=Anti-Rockism's Hall of Fame|work=[[The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor =\n |width = 22%\n |salign = right\n |align = right\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 89%\n}}\n\nPop music has been dominated by the American and (from the mid-1960s) British [[music industry|music industries]], whose influence has made pop music something of an international monoculture, but most regions and countries have their own form of pop music, sometimes producing local versions of wider trends, and lending them local characteristics.<ref>J. Kun, ''Audiotopia: Music, Race, and America'' (Berkeley, CA: University of California Press, 2005), {{ISBN|0-520-24424-9}}, p. 201.</ref> Some of these trends (for example [[Europop]]) have had a significant impact of the development of the genre.<ref name=Firth2002>\"Star profiles\" in S. Frith, W. Stray and J. Street, ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001), {{ISBN|0-521-55660-0}}, pp. 199\u2013200.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Grove Music Online'', \"Western-derived pop styles, whether coexisting with or marginalizing distinctively local genres, have spread throughout the world and have come to constitute stylistic common denominators in global commercial music cultures\".<ref name=PManuel>P. Manuel, \"Pop. Non-Western cultures 1. Global dissemination\", ''Grove Music Online'', retrieved 14 March 2010.</ref> Some non-Western countries, such as Japan, have developed a thriving pop music industry, most of which is devoted to Western-style pop. Japan has for several years produced a greater quantity of music than everywhere except the US.{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}}<ref name=PManuel/> The spread of Western-style pop music has been interpreted variously as representing processes of Americanization, [[Radio Homogenization|homogenization]], modernization, creative appropriation, [[cultural imperialism]], or a more general process of [[globalization]].<ref name=PManuel/>\n\nIn Korea, pop music's influence has led to the birth of [[boy bands]] and [[girl groups]] which have gained overseas renown through both their music and aesthetics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/yodona/2015/12/03/565f220b46163ff4308b45c9.html|title=K-Pop, la m\u00fasica y la moda 'rarita' coreana que arrasa la red|date=December 3, 2015|website=ELMUNDO}}</ref> Korean [[co-ed groups]] (mixed gender groups) have not been as successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2016/08/25/why-arent-there-many-mixed-gender-k-pop-groups|title=Why aren't there many mixed gender K-pop groups?|website=SBS PopAsia}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pop music|Music}}\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[Origins of rock and roll]]\n* [[Popular music pedagogy]]\n* [[List of popular music genres]]\n* [[History of music]]\n* [[Public domain music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno|Adorno, Theodor W.]], (1942) \"On Popular Music\", Institute of Social Research.\n* Bell, John L., (2000) ''The Singing Thing: A Case for Congregational Song'', GIA Publications, {{ISBN|1-57999-100-9}}\n* Bindas, Kenneth J., (1992) ''America's Musical Pulse: Popular Music in Twentieth-Century Society'', Praeger.\n* [[Donald Clarke (writer)|Clarke, Donald]], (1995) ''The Rise and Fall of Popular Music'', St Martin's Press. [https://web.archive.org/web/20071231045026/http://www.musicweb.uk.net/RiseandFall/index.htm ]\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (1999) ''Valuing Pop Music: Institutions, Values and Economics'', Eburon.\n* Dolfsma, Wilfred, (2004) ''Institutional Economics and the Formation of Preferences: The Advent of Pop Music'', Edward Elgar Publishing.\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]], Straw, Will, Street, John, eds, (2001), ''The Cambridge Companion to Pop and Rock'', Cambridge University Press,\n* [[Simon Frith|Frith, Simon]] (2004) ''Popular Music: Critical Concepts in Media and Cultural Studies'', Routledge.\n* [[Charlie Gillett|Gillett, Charlie]], (1970) ''The Sound of the City. The Rise of Rock and Roll'', Outerbridge & Dienstfrey.\n* Hatch, David and Stephen Millward, (1987), ''From Blues to Rock: an Analytical History of Pop Music'', Manchester University Press, {{ISBN|0-7190-1489-1}}\n* Johnson, Julian, (2002) ''Who Needs Classical Music?: Cultural Choice and Musical Value'', Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0-19-514681-6}}.\n* [[Jeff Kent (author)|Kent, Jeff]], (1983) ''The Rise and Fall of Rock'', Witan Books, {{ISBN|0-9508981-0-4}}.\n* Lonergan, David F., (2004) ''Hit Records, 1950\u20131975'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0-8108-5129-6}}.\n* Maultsby, Portia K., (7907) ''Intra- and International Identities in American Popular Music'', Trading Culture.\n* [[Richard Middleton (musicologist)|Middleton, Richard]], (1990) ''Studying Popular Music'', Open University Press.\n* Negus, Bob, (1999) ''Music Genres and Corporate Cultures'', Routledge, {{ISBN|0-415-17399-X}}.\n* [[Henry Pleasants (music critic)|Pleasants, Henry]] (1969) ''Serious Music and All That Jazz'', Simon & Schuster.\n* [[Lillian Roxon|Roxon, Lillian]], (1969) ''Rock Encyclopedia'', Grosset & Dunlap.\n* Shuker, Roy, (2002) ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', Routledge, (2nd edn.) {{ISBN|0-415-28425-2}}.\n* Starr, Larry & Waterman, Christopher, (2002) ''American Popular Music: From Minstrelsy to MTV'', Oxford University Press.\n* Watkins, S. Craig, (2005) ''Hip Hop Matters: Politics, Pop Culture, and the Struggle for the Soul of a Movement'', Beacon Press, {{ISBN|0-8070-0982-2}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Pop music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407053620/http://musiclife.mobi/filelist/1017/sabrang_%282017%29_mp3/new2old/1 The Consumption of Music and the Expression of Values: A Social Economic Explanation for the Advent of Pop Music], Wilfred Dolfsma, ''[[American Journal of Economics and Sociology]]'', October 1999.\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Media culture}}\n{{Western world}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pop Music}}\n[[Category:Pop music| ]]\n[[Category:Western culture]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n", "name_user": "Florian Blaschke", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTechnology and media:punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pop_music"}
{"title_page": "1998 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|85th edition of cycling Grand Tour}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1998 Tour de France\n| image              = Route of the 1998 Tour de France.png\n| image_size         = 360px\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1998 Tour de France\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1998 Tour de France\n| date               = 11 July \u2013 2 August\n| stages             = 21 + Prologue\n| distance           = 3875\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 92h 49' 46\"\n| first              = [[Marco Pantani]]\n| first_nat          = ITA\n| first_team         = {{ct|UNO|1998}}\n| first_color        = yellow\n| second             = [[Jan Ullrich]]\n| second_nat         = GER\n| second_team        = {{ct|THR|1998}}\n| third              = [[Bobby Julich]]\n| third_nat          = USA\n| third_team         = {{ct|COF|1998}}\n| points             = [[Erik Zabel]]\n| points_nat         = GER\n| points_team        = {{ct|THR|1998}}\n| points_color       = green\n| mountains          = [[Christophe Rinero]]\n| mountains_nat      = FRA\n| mountains_team     = {{ct|COF|1998}}\n| mountains_color    = polkadot\n| youth              = [[Jan Ullrich]]\n| youth_nat          = GER\n| youth_team         = {{ct|THR|1998}}\n| team               = {{ct|COF|1998}}\n| combativity        = [[Jacky Durand]]\n| combativity_nat    = FRA\n| combativity_team   = {{ct|CSO|1998}}\n| combativity_color  = red_number\n| previous           = [[1997 Tour de France|1997]]\n| next               = [[1999 Tour de France|1999]]\n}}\nThe '''1998 Tour de France''' was the 85th edition of the [[Tour de France]], one of cycling's [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]] and generally considered to be the most famous bike race in the world.{{sfn|Hanold|2012|p=13}} The {{convert|3,875|km|mi|abbr=on}} race was composed of 21 stages and a prologue. It started on 11 July in [[Ireland]] before taking an anti-clockwise route through France to finish in [[Paris]] on 2 August. [[Marco Pantani]] of {{ct|UNO|1998}} won the overall [[General classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], with {{ct|THR|1998}}'s [[Jan Ullrich]], the defending champion, and {{ct|COF|1998}} rider [[Bobby Julich]] finishing on the podium in second and third respectively.\n\nThe general classification leader's yellow jersey was first awarded to [[Chris Boardman]] of the {{ct|GAN|1998a}} team, who won the prologue in Dublin. Following a crash by Boardman on stage 2 that caused his withdrawal, Ullrich's [[Sprinter (cycling)|sprinter]] teammate [[Erik Zabel]] took the race lead. He lost it the next stage to {{ct|ALM|1998}}'s [[Bo Hamburger]], who took it after being in a [[Breakaway (cycling)|breakaway]]. The day after, the yellow jersey switched to another rider from the same breakaway, Boardman's teammate [[Stuart O'Grady]], who took vital seconds from time bonuses gained in [[intermediate sprint]]s. He held it for a further three stages, until pre-race favourite Ullrich won stage 7's individual time trial, moving him into the overall lead. The next day, [[Laurent Desbiens]] of {{ct|COF|1998}} finished in a breakaway with a large enough margin to put him in the yellow jersey. Ullrich regained the race lead two stages later as the Tour went into the Pyrenees. Following his poor showing in the opening week, Pantani placed second and first, respectively, on the two Pyreneean stages. He then won the first stage in the Alps, stage 15, to replace Ullrich in the yellow jersey, which he maintained until the race's conclusion.\n\nZabel won his third consecutive Tour [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]] and Julich's teammate [[Christophe Rinero]], fourth overall, was the winner of the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]]. Ullrich was the [[young rider classification in the Tour de France|best young rider]] and the [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|most combative]] was {{ct|CSO|1998}}'s [[Jacky Durand]]. The [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was won by {{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}. [[Tom Steels]] of {{ct|MAP|1998}} won the most stages, with four.\n\nThe race was marred throughout its run by a doping scandal, commonly known as the [[Festina affair]]. Before the Tour began, [[Willy Voet]], ''[[soigneur]]'' of the [[Festina (cycling team)|Festina team]], was arrested at the Franco-Belgian border when doping products were found in his car. The affair broadened and the team was expelled after top personnel admitted to widespread doping. Police raids on numerous teams during the course of the race led to two riders' strikes and the withdrawal of several teams and riders. Due to the controversy, the race became known by the nickname \"'''Tour de Farce'''\". In July 2013, retrospective tests for [[recombinant EPO]] made in 2004 were made public, revealing that 44 out of 60 of samples returned positive tests.\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1998 Tour de France}}\n\n[[File:Dubl\u00edn - Trinity College - 20170826172210.jpg|thumb|alt=A gated large stone building with a clock tower on its roof|[[Trinity College Dublin]] in Ireland hosted the team presentation ceremony on 10 July.]]\nThe organisers of the Tour, [[Amaury Sport Organisation]] (ASO), decided to reduce the number of [[Cycling team|teams]] from 22 to 21 for the 1998 Tour. This was done to counteract the high number of crashes in the opening week of the race seen in recent editions, which was associated with the large number of riders.<ref name=\"volkskrant-route\">{{cite news |title=Ullrich enthousiast, Virenque in mineur |trans-title=Ullrich enthusiastic, Virenque in minor |url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/ullrich-enthousiast-virenque-in-mineur~bd8b3f90/ |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[De Volkskrant]] |date=24 October 1997 |language=Dutch |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416231704/https://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/ullrich-enthousiast-virenque-in-mineur~bd8b3f90/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first round of squads that were invited were the first sixteen teams in the [[UCI Road World Rankings|ranking system]] of the ''[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]'' (UCI), cycling's governing body, on 1 January 1998, provided that they were still in the top twenty after transfers were factored into the calculation.<ref name=\"letour-sporting-aspects\">{{cite web|title=1998 Tour de France \u2013 Sporting aspects|url=http://www.letour.fr:80/tour98us/particularites.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=24 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980526070652/http://www.letour.fr/tour98us/particularites.html|archivedate=26 May 1998|url-status=dead}}</ref> All these sixteen teams fulfilled this requirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/feb98/feb6.html|title=News for February 6, 1998: Tour 1998|date=6 February 1998|accessdate=21 August 2011|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025181403/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/feb98/feb6.html|archive-date=25 October 2012|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> On 19 June, the ASO gave [[Wild card (sports)|wildcard]] invitations to {{ct|ASI|1998}}, {{ct|COF|1998}}, {{ct|RIS|1998}} and {{ct|VIT|1998}}, with {{ct|AUB|1998}} receiving a special invitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/jun98/jun19.html|title=News for June 19, 1998: In the Tour de France|date=19 June 1998|accessdate=21 August 2011|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025181408/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/jun98/jun19.html|archive-date=25 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The presentation of the teams&nbsp;\u2013 where the members of each team's roster are introduced in front of the media and local dignitaries&nbsp;\u2013 took place outside the Front Gate of [[Trinity College Dublin]] in Ireland on the evening before the [[Prologue (cycling)|prologue]] [[Race stage|stage]], which began at the college.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=30}}\n\nEach squad was allowed a maximum of nine riders, resulting in a start list total of 189 riders.<ref name=\"uci-teams\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Teams|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/teams.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516193702/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/teams.htm|archivedate=16 May 2019}}</ref> Of these, 51 were riding the Tour de France for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Debutants|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/debutants|website=ProCyclingStats|access-date=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512185712/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/debutants|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The riders came from 22 countries, with the majority of them coming from France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"uci-teams\" /> [[J\u00f6rg Jaksche]] ({{ct|POL|1998}}) was the youngest rider at 21 years and 353 days on the day of the prologue, and the oldest was [[Massimo Podenzana]] ({{ct|UNO|1998}}) at 36 years and 347 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Youngest competitors|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/youngest-competitors|website=ProCyclingStats|access-date=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512185444/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/youngest-competitors|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The {{ct|POL|1998|nolink=yes}} cyclists had the youngest average age while the riders on {{ct|UNO|1998|nolink=yes}} had the oldest.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Average team age|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/average-team-age|website=ProCyclingStats|access-date=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512185502/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/startlist/average-team-age|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe teams entering the race were:<ref name=\"uci-teams\" />\n\n'''Qualified teams'''\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{ct|GCE|1998}}\n*{{ct|ALM|1998}}\n*{{ct|FES|1998}}\n*{{ct|FDJ|1998}}\n*{{ct|C.A|1998a}}\n*{{ct|KEL|1998}}\n*{{ct|SIL|1998}}\n*{{ct|MAP|1998}}\n*{{ct|UNO|1998}}\n*{{ct|ONC|1998}}\n*{{ct|POL|1998}}\n*{{ct|RAB|1998}}\n*{{ct|SAE|1998}}\n*{{ct|THR|1998}}\n*{{ct|TVM|1998}}\n*{{ct|DSC|1998}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Invited teams'''\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{ct|ASI|1998}}\n*{{ct|AUB|1998}}\n*{{ct|COF|1998}}\n*{{ct|RIS|1998}}\n*{{ct|VIT|1998}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Pre-race favourites==\n[[File:Jan Ullrich, 1997.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Jan Ullrich riding a bicycle wearing a yellow jersey|[[Jan Ullrich]] (''pictured during the [[1997 Tour de France|1997 Tour]]'') was considered the main favourite for the [[General classification in the Tour de France|general classification]].]]\n[[Jan Ullrich]] ({{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}}) was the defending champion, having won the [[1997 Tour de France|1997 edition]]'s overall [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]] with an over nine-minute lead.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=113}} His Telekom team was considered as \"clearly the squad to beat\",{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=5}} having won the previous two editions with [[Bjarne Riis]] and Ullrich respectively.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=77}} The 1997 Tour had seen a contest for leadership between Telekom's two captains, but for 1998 this had been resolved in Ullrich's favour.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=6}} During the winter break, Ullrich's training was impaired by the consequences of the fame and fortune that came with his Tour win,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=243}}<ref name=\"uci-intro\">{{cite web|last=Kelly|first=Seamus|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Intro|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/intro.htm|accessdate=5 June 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605011322/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/intro.htm|archivedate=5 June 2019}}</ref> and his weight had increased from {{convert|73|kg|lbs|abbr=on}} to {{convert|87|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=6}} In March 1998, ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'' headlined an article with \"Ullrich is fat\", highlighting that by this point he was still {{convert|8|kg|lbs|abbr=on}} over the weight he had during the previous Tour.<ref name=\"ullrich-weight\">{{cite news |last=Arribas |first=Carlos |title=Ullrich est\u00e1 gordo |trans-title=Ullrich is fat |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1998/03/16/deportes/890002833_850215.html |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=16 March 1998 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416103955/https://elpais.com/diario/1998/03/16/deportes/890002833_850215.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> His preparation was worsened when he suffered a cold during [[1998 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]], having to retire from the race.<ref name=\"ullrich-weight\" /> However, Ullrich performed well in both the [[1998 Tour de Suisse|Tour de Suisse]] and the [[Route du Sud]] directly before the start of the Tour, erasing doubt over his form.<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\">{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Cycling; Ullrich ready to roll after tasting success |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/07/sports/cycling-ullrich-ready-to-roll-after-tasting-success.html |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=7 July 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416093817/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/07/sports/cycling-ullrich-ready-to-roll-after-tasting-success.html |archivedate=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was therefore thought to be the clear favourite going into the 1998 Tour,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=243}}<ref name=\"uci-intro\" />{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=5\u20136}}{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=181}} with ''El Pa\u00eds'' going so far as to write that \"we can no longer speak of an open Tour, of a deck of suitors. There is talk of Ullrich, and then of the others.\"<ref name=\"pais-fav\">{{cite news |last=Arribas |first=Carlos |title=Ullrich y los dem\u00e1s |trans-title=Ullrich and the others |url=https://elpais.com/diario/1998/07/11/deportes/900108009_850215.html |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=11 July 1998 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416102451/https://elpais.com/diario/1998/07/11/deportes/900108009_850215.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The route of the race was considered to be an advantage to Ullrich as well, with many time-trial kilometres and comparably few mountain passes.<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" /> The veteran Riis, who had raced the 1997 Tour with a cold, was seen as a capable backup option for the team.<ref name=\"uci-intro\" />\n\nThe strongest challenge was expected to come from {{ct|FES|1998|nolink=yes}},<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" /> which led the UCI team ranking prior to the start of the Tour.<ref name=\"uci-rankings-07-07-98\">{{cite web|title=UCI Road Rankings \u2013 7 July 1998|url=http://www.uci.ch/english/road/data/men_980705.pdf|accessdate=6 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|date=7 July 1998|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000830115753/http://www.uci.ch/english/road/data/men_980705.pdf|archivedate=30 August 2000}}</ref> Their leading rider, [[Richard Virenque]], had finished second to Ullrich the year before. The two long [[individual time trial]]s were expected not to be in Virenque's favour, since he did not excel in the discipline.<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" /> He was however a very good [[Climbing specialist|climber]], having won the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] in the four previous Tours.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=120}} The team was further strengthened by the arrival of [[Alex Z\u00fclle]] in the 1998 season, winner of the two previous editions of the three-week [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] of Spain, the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], who was considered to be a competitor for overall victory in his own right.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=6\u20137}}{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=26}} He was a leading pre-race favourite at Italy's Grand Tour, the [[1998 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]],{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|pp=28\u201328}}<ref name=\"cn-apotheosis\">{{cite web |last=Farrand |first=Stephen |title=Giro d'Italia: The apotheosis of Marco Pantani |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/giro-ditalia-the-apotheosis-of-marco-pantani/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=16 April 2019 |date=26 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416105133/http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/giro-ditalia-the-apotheosis-of-marco-pantani/ |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> one month prior, winning two of the three time trial stages and leading the race before he faltered badly in the final mountain stages to end the race in 14th overall.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|pp=28\u201328}}<ref name=\"cn-giro\">{{cite news|title=Giro d'Italia, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 22 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/may98/giro98/stage22.html|access-date=13 May 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=7 June 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606222335/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/may98/giro98/stage22.html|archive-date=6 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another possible contender from Festina was [[Laurent Dufaux]], who had finished fourth overall in [[1996 Tour de France|1996]] and ninth in 1997.<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" />\n\n[[Marco Pantani]] ({{ct|UNO|1998|nolink=yes}}) was considered the \"dominant climber in the sport\" at the time.<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" /> In June, he had taken an \"exceptionally impressive\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=7}} overall victory at the Giro.<ref name=\"cn-apotheosis\" /> Of his three appearances in the Tour up to that point, he had finished third in two of them, including in 1997.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=36}} When the Tour's route was announced in October 1997, Pantani expressed dissatisfaction with the amount of time trials and the fact that the race featured only two mountain-top finishes. Since the route was not to his liking, he originally had shown no interest in riding the race. Following his victory at the Giro, Pantani raced only once, a [[criterium]] race in [[Bologna]]. His decision to ride the Tour was not made until [[Luciano Pezzi]], his closest confidant and an important figure at Mercatone Uno, died suddenly in late June. Pantani decided to go to the Tour in honour of Pezzi, but had done very little training beforehand.{{sfn|Friebe|2014|pp=144\u2013146}} A further disadvantage to Pantani was his lack of a strong [[domestique]], unlike Ullrich and Virenque.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=36}}\n\nA returning pre-race favourite from the 1997 Tour was [[time trialist]] [[Abraham Olano]]; in that race, he won the final time trial stage and placed fourth overall.<ref name=\"uci-intro\" />{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=34}} He led the experienced {{ct|BAN|1998|nolink=yes}} team, who took [[Miguel Indur\u00e1in]] to his five straight Tour wins between [[1991 Tour de France|1991]] and [[1995 Tour de France|1995]],{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=34}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=110}} and had been seen as his successor.<ref name=\"uci-intro\" />{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=34}} His weakness was thought to be his lack of strength on steep climbs.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=34}} In his final race leading up to the Tour, the [[1998 Volta a Catalunya|Volta a Catalunya]], he performed poorly in the high mountains,<ref name=\"uci-intro\" /> and as a result was only seen as a podium contender.<ref name=\"uci-intro\" />{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=34}} Banesto also fielded [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez]], who as a strong mountain rider was considered a \"major threat\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=7}}\n\nThe final rider noted as a leading contender, named \"the outsider\", was the {{ct|ONC|1998|nolink=yes}} team leader [[Laurent Jalabert]], a complete [[Bicycling terminology#all-rounder|all-rounder]] who excelled in all road cycling disciplines.{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|p=29}} Although he was the [[1997 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Men's time trial|reigning time trial world champion]] and the clear first in the UCI individual ranking before the Tour,<ref name=\"uci-intro\" /><ref name=\"uci-rankings-07-07-98\" /> he had only aimed to match his overall placing of fourth in 1995.<ref name=\"uci-intro\" /> The riders also named as outside favourites for overall victory were [[Michael Boogerd]] ({{ct|RAB|1998|nolink=yes}}),<ref name=\"nytimes-preview\" /> {{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}} riders [[Francesco Casagrande]] and [[Bobby Julich]], [[Evgeni Berzin]] ({{ct|FDJ|1998|nolink=yes}}), [[Fernando Escart\u00edn]] ({{ct|KEL|1998|nolink=yes}}), and [[Chris Boardman]] ({{ct|GAN|1998a|nolink=yes}}).{{sfn|Whittle et al.|1998|pp=40\u201344}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n{{main|1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11|1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n\n[[File:Col du Galibier 3 (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=A road summit hairpin with mountains in the background|The [[Col du Galibier]] Alpine pass on stage 15 was the [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point reached in the Tour]] at {{convert|2645|m|ft|abbr=on}}.]]\nThe route of the 1998 Tour de France was officially announced during a presentation at the [[Palais des congr\u00e8s de Paris|Palais des congr\u00e8s]] in Paris on 23 October 1997.<ref name=\"irish-route\">{{cite news |title=The Tour de France |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-tour-de-france-1.119017 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=24 October 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162816/https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-tour-de-france-1.119017|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes-route\">{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Cycling: Tour de France; 1998 race too flat for Virenque's tastes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/24/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-1998-race-too-flat-for-virenque-s-tastes.html |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=24 October 1997 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416220902/https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/24/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-1998-race-too-flat-for-virenque-s-tastes.html |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> First negotiations about a potential start of the race in Ireland took place in October 1996, with the Irish government securing funding of IR\u00a32 million to host the event.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunne |first=Jim |title=Ireland may host start of 1998 Tour de France |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland-may-host-start-of-1998-tour-de-france-1.93761 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=9 October 1996|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162931/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland-may-host-start-of-1998-tour-de-france-1.93761|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The opening stages (known as the ''[[List of Tour de France Grands D\u00e9parts|Grand D\u00e9part]]'') in Ireland were confirmed in early April 1997.<ref>{{cite news |last=McArdle |first=Jim |title=Irish stages confirmed for 1998 Tour de France |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/irish-stages-confirmed-for-1998-tour-de-france-1.58384 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=3 April 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162944/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/irish-stages-confirmed-for-1998-tour-de-france-1.58384|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Irish officials expected the race to bring in IR\u00a330 million to the local economy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dunne |first=Jim |title=Tour worth \u00a330m to economy \u2013 Kenny |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/tour-worth-30m-to-economy-kenny-1.58741 |accessdate=16 April 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=4 April 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162953/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/tour-worth-30m-to-economy-kenny-1.58741|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the first time that the Tour visited Ireland.<ref name=\"volkskrant-route\" /> The race paid tribute to two famous former Irish professional cyclists: On the day before the prologue, a commemoration service was held in [[Kilmacanogue]] for [[Seamus Elliott]], the first Irish rider to ride the Tour and win a stage.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first1=Tim |title=Service commemorates Shay Elliott |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/service-commemorates-shay-elliott-1.172172 |accessdate=9 May 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=11 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618163004/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/service-commemorates-shay-elliott-1.172172|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> During stage 2 of the race, the route went through [[Carrick-on-Suir]], the hometown of [[Sean Kelly (cyclist)|Sean Kelly]], four-time winner of the [[Points classification in the Tour de France|Tour's points classification]].{{sfn|Smith|2009|p=148}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Watterson |first1=Johnny |title=Race whizzes through Carrick in tribute to a great Irish sportsman |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/race-whizzes-through-carrick-in-tribute-to-a-great-irish-sportsman-1.173042 |accessdate=9 May 2019 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=14 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618163250/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/race-whizzes-through-carrick-in-tribute-to-a-great-irish-sportsman-1.173042|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Stage 2 also commemorated the 200th anniversary of French troops landing at [[Killala Bay]] during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].{{sfn|Smith|2009|p=147}}\n\nThe 1998 Tour was pushed back one week from its original start date, so as not to overlap too much with the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], also held in France, which ended on 12 July, one day after the prologue.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=116}} The {{convert|3875|km|0|abbr=on}}-race lasted 23 days, including the rest day, and ended on 2 August.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=89}}<ref name=\"uci-route\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/default.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516193726/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/default.htm|archive-date=16 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The longest [[Mass start|mass-start]] stage was the fourth at {{convert|252|km|0|abbr=on}}, and stage 20 was the shortest at {{convert|125|km|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"uci-route\" /> The race contained three individual time trials, one of which was the prologue, totalling {{convert|115.6|km|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=243}} Of the remaining stages, twelve were officially classified as flat, two as mountain and five as high mountain.<ref name=\"letour-sporting-aspects\" /> There were only two summit finishes,{{sfn|Moore|2014|p=181}} which were both at ski resorts, one at [[Plateau de Beille]] on stage 11 and another on stage 15 at [[Les Deux Alpes]].<ref name=volkskrant-route /> The [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2642|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col du Galibier]] mountain pass on stage 15.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=177\u2013178}}<ref name=\"cn-15\">{{cite news|title=Tour de France, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 15 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage15.html|access-date=13 May 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=27 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110909054249/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage15.html|archive-date=9 September 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> It was among five ''[[hors cat\u00e9gorie]]'' (beyond category) rated climbs in the race.<ref name=\"uci-10\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Stage 10|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_10.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516210027/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_10.htm|archivedate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"uci-11\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Stage 11|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_11.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516210031/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_11.htm|archivedate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"uci-15\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Stage 15|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_15.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516210043/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_15.htm|archivedate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"uci-16\">{{cite web|title=Le Tour de France report \u2013 Stage 16|url=http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_16.htm|accessdate=16 May 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516210110/http://62.50.72.82/english/tdf/tdf_98_16.htm|archivedate=16 May 2019}}</ref> Cycling journalist [[Samuel Abt]] considered the route easier than the 1997 edition.<ref name=\"nytimes-route\" /> Tour director [[Jean-Marie Leblanc]] countered criticism by Virenque and Pantani that the race was not mountainous enough, saying: \"The course is tough enough with 23 mountains. That is eight more than last year.\"<ref name=\"volkskrant-route\" />\n\nThe Tour started with a prologue time trial around the streets of [[Dublin]]. Stage 1 was a loop that returned to the city, with the following stage travelling down the Irish eastern coast towards [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref name=\"irish-route\" /> The riders then travelled to France by plane,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=43}} with the team vehicles and equipment following by sea.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=51}} Just as the year before, the Tour took a counter-clockwise route through France.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=12}} The course in France started in [[Roscoff]] in the north-western region of [[Brittany]], with three stages taking the race to the centre of the country at [[Ch\u00e2teauroux]]. Stage 6 moved the Tour into the [[Massif Central]] highlands, which host the next stage. Two transitional stages to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] then placed the race in the foothills of the [[Pyrenees]], where two stages took place. Following the rest day, a three-stage journey crossed the south to three further stages in the [[Alps]]. The next stage took the Tour through the [[Jura Mountains]] to Switzerland, with the following stage moving back into France, specifically to the region of [[Burgundy]], where the penultimate stage took place. After a long transfer to the outskirts of Paris, the race ended with the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es stage in the Tour de France|Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es stage]].{{sfn|Bacon|2014|p=210}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"letour-sporting-aspects\" /><ref name=\"uci-route\" />{{sfn|Bacon|2014|p=210}}<ref name=\"letour-stage-winners\">{{cite web|title=The history of the Tour de France \u2013 Year 1998 \u2013 The stage winners|url=http://histo.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1998/vainqueurs.html|work=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Prologue|P]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |11 July || [[Dublin]] (Ireland)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|5.6|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Chris Boardman]]|GBR}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |12 July || [[Dublin]] (Ireland)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|180.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |13 July || [[Enniscorthy]] (Ireland) to [[Cork (city)|Cork]] (Ireland)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|205.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[J\u00e1n Svorada]]|CZE}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |14 July || [[Roscoff]] to [[Lorient]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|169|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jens Heppner]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |15 July || [[Plouay]] to [[Cholet]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|252|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jeroen Blijlevens]]|NED}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |16 July || [[Cholet]] to [[Ch\u00e2teauroux]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|228.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Mario Cipollini]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17 July || [[La Ch\u00e2tre]] to [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|204.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Mario Cipollini]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |18 July || [[Meyrignac-l'\u00c9glise]] to [[Corr\u00e8ze]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|58|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |19 July || [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]] to [[Montauban]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|190.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jacky Durand]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |20 July || [[Montauban]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|210|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on van Bon]]|NED}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |21 July || [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Luchon]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|196.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Rodolfo Massi]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |22 July || [[Luchon]] to [[Plateau de Beille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|170|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marco Pantani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Ari\u00e8ge (department)|Ari\u00e8ge]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July || [[Tarascon-sur-Ari\u00e8ge]] to [[Cap d'Agde]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|190|km|0|abbr=on}}{{efn|Stage 12 was originally scheduled to be {{convert|206|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, but as a result of the delayed start due to a riders' strike, the stage was shortened to {{convert|190|km|0|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=142}}}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25 July || [[Frontignan la Peyrade]] to [[Carpentras]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|196|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Daniele Nardello]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July || [[Valr\u00e9as]] to [[Grenoble]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|186.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Stuart O'Grady]]|AUS}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |27 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Les Deux Alpes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|189|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marco Pantani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |28 July || [[Vizille]] to [[Albertville]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|204|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |29 July || [[Albertville]] to [[Aix-les-Bains]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|149|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014{{efn|name=\"note-stage-17\"|Stage 17 was cancelled and did not count as the riders held a strike due to the developing [[Festina affair]].<ref name=\"letour-stage-17\">{{cite web|title=Stage 17 cancelled|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=24 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990203085256/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/|archivedate=3 February 1999}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 July || [[Aix-les-Bains]] to [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] (Switzerland)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|218.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |31 July || [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] (Switzerland) to [[Autun]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|242|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Magnus B\u00e4ckstedt]]|SWE}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1 August || [[Montceau-les-Mines]] to [[Le Creusot]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|52|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2 August || [[Melun]] to [[Paris]] ([[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es stage in the Tour de France|Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]])|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|147.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|3875|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=89}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11|1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n\n===Pre-Tour revelations===\nOn 4 March 1998, a truck belonging to the Dutch {{ct|TVM|1998|nolink=yes}} team had been seized by [[customs officer]]s in [[Reims]], France, revealing 104 vials of recombinant [[erythropoietin]] (EPO), a drug with performance-enhancing effects. The two [[Bicycle mechanic|mechanics]] in the truck were released and the vials were taken by the police, who said they had more \"important matters\" to be concerned with.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=2}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=12}} During the [[1998 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], a race held two weeks before the start of the Tour, [[Christophe Moreau]] of Festina tested positive for the anabolic steroid [[mesterolone]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9: De las Cuevas leader |url=https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/1998/06/11/185857-dauphine-libere-de-las-cuevas-leader.html |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]] |date=11 June 1998 |language=French}}</ref> The UCI accepted Festina's explanation that the positive test was a result of the influence of a team masseur, and Moreau was allowed to start the Tour de France.{{sfn|Woodland|2003|p=155}}\n\nThree days before the start of the Tour, on 8 July, [[Willy Voet]], a ''[[soigneur]]'' (team assistant) with the Festina squad, was stopped by customs officers driving along a back road on the [[Belgium\u2013France border|Franco\u2013Belgian border]].{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=1}} A routine check revealed that he carried a large quantity of performance-enhancing drugs with him.{{efn|The content of Voet's car was \"82 vials of Saizen ([[somatropin]], or [[human growth hormone]]), 60 capsules of [[Pantestone]] ([[epitestosterone]]), 248 vials of physiological serum, 8 pre-filled syringes containing hepatitis-A vaccine, 2 boxes of 30 Hyperlipen tablets (to lower the amount of fat in the blood), 4 further doses of somatropin, 4 ampoules of Synacthene (to increase the rate at which [[Corticosteroid|corticoid hormones]] are secreted by the adrenal gland) and 2 vials of [[amphetamine]]\" as well as \"234 doses of recombinant human [[erythropoietin]]\".{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=117}}}} He was thereafter placed under arrest, initially claiming they were \"for personal use\".{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=1}} The following day, police carried out a search of Festina's headquarters in [[Meyzieu]], close to Lyon.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} On the day before the prologue, a judicial inquiry was opened by the public prosecutor's office and Voet was held for investigation,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} with the story also breaking to the media.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=117}} The Tour's organisation as well as Festina were quick to dismiss the news as having nothing to do with the race.<ref name=\"nytimes_prol\">{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Cycling; Boardman wins as drug case arises |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/12/sports/cycling-boardman-wins-as-drug-case-arises.html |accessdate=12 May 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 July 1998|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512122629/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/12/sports/cycling-boardman-wins-as-drug-case-arises.html|archivedate=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=246}}\n\n===Early stages in Ireland===\n[[File:1998 Tour de France, Prologue map.png|thumb|left|alt=An illustrated map of Dublin with the route of the prologue time trial|The {{convert|5.6|km|abbr=on}} route of the [[Prologue (cycling)|prologue]] time trial around the streets of [[Dublin]], won by [[Chris Boardman]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a}})]]\nChris Boardman covered the {{convert|5.6|km|mi|abbr=on}} route of the prologue time trial fastest with a time of 6:12.36 minutes,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=31}} gaining his third Tour prologue victory.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=27}} The second, third and fourth-placed finishers Abraham Olano, Laurent Jalabert and Bobby Julich all had times that were four seconds more, with Jan Ullrich finishing sixth, five seconds behind Boardman.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=31}} Marco Pantani meanwhile had not bothered to preview the course and finished 181st out of the 189 starters, 48 seconds slower than the winning time.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=118}} Boardman was awarded the yellow and green jerseys as the leader of both the general and points classification respectively.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\">{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Leaders overview|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216224428/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Tom Steels]] outsprinted [[Erik Zabel]] in stage 1's [[bunch sprint]] finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=35}} Steels came to the Tour with the full support of his {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}} squad for the sprints, unlike Zabel's {{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}} who were focused on Ullrich's pursuit for overall victory.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=43}} [[Mario Cipollini]] ({{ct|SAE|1998|nolink=yes}}), a favourite for the stage win, was held up {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} from the end when he was involved in a crash caused by his teammate.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Wicklow Welcomes Tour De France |series=Sunday Sport |date=12 July 1998 |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0703/976039-tour-de-france-in-wicklow/ |accessdate=10 June 2019 |network=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |last=Willoughby |first=Roy (reporter) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529042355/https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0703/976039-tour-de-france-in-wicklow/ |archivedate=29 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=33}} Steels took the lead of the points classification from Boardman, who retained the overall lead.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Steels's teammate [[Stefano Zanini]] was the first of a seven-rider [[Breakaway (cycling)|breakaway]] group to reach the summit of the [[Wicklow Gap]] mountain pass, claiming the Tour's first available mountains classification points and the first [[polka dot|polka-dot]] jersey.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" />{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=34\u201335}}\n\nUnlike other general classification favourites, who always rode at the front of the [[peloton]] (main group), Pantani spent the first days of the Tour at the back, surrounded by his teammates.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=118}}{{efn|Common cycling tactics dictate that riders should stay towards the front of the peloton to minimise the risk of being involved in a crash.{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=148}}}} This almost cost him, when during stage 2, which was raced largely on the wide [[N25 road (Ireland)|N25]] road,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=39\u201340}} [[crosswind]]s split the field into several [[Echelon formation|echelons]]. Pantani was caught out and only came back when yellow jersey-wearer Boardman crashed heavily. In the aftermath, the peloton slowed down, allowing Pantani to catch back up.{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=142}} Boardman meanwhile hit his head badly on a stone wall beside the road. He was taken to hospital and had to abandon the Tour.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pogatchnik |first=Shawn |title=Britain's Boardman out of Tour after crash |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/boardman.htm |url-access=limited |accessdate=12 May 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=13 July 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162605/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/boardman.htm|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}} rider [[J\u00e1n Svorada]] was involved in a crash with {{convert|15|km|abbr=on}} to go, but was able to recover and win the bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=42\u201343}} Zabel, who before the stage stood in eighth position overall,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=38}} had collected enough time bonuses in the [[intermediate sprint]]s to take the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=40\u201341}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Move to France and evolving doping scandal===\n[[File:Richard VIRENQUE.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Richard Virenque wearing a white, red and yellow cap|[[Richard Virenque]] (''pictured in 1993''), the leader of the {{ct|FES|1998}} team, which was expelled from the Tour after stage 6 following its management's admission to [[Doping in sport|doping]].]]\n{{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Jens Heppner]] won stage 3 from a two-rider sprint with [[Xavier Jan]] of {{ct|FDJ|1998|nolink=yes}}, after the pair had broken away late from a nine-rider breakaway. [[Bo Hamburger]] of {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}}, who won two of the three intermediate sprints whilst in the escape group, took the overall lead.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=47\u201352}} Svorada took the lead of the points classification, with Festina's [[Pascal Herv\u00e9]] claiming the mountains classification lead.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> The second and third placers in the now much changed general classification also came from the breakaway, with [[George Hincapie]] ({{ct|DSC|1998|nolink=yes}}) two seconds down on Hamburger, and [[Stuart O'Grady]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) a further second behind.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=52\u201353}} Hincapie and O'Grady went head to head for the time bonuses in stage 4's three intermediate sprints, with O'Grady winning two of them to end the day with an eleven-second overall advantage over both Hincapie and Hamburger. The stage was won by [[Jeroen Blijlevens]] (TVM) from an uphill bunch sprint at [[Cholet]] in the [[Loire Valley]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=77}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=55\u201360}} Cipollini suffered his third crash of the Tour at the end of stage 4,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=58}} accumulating eight separate injuries,{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=81}} but was able to avoid the multiple crashes in the next stage to win the bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=79}} Svorada was disqualified for causing a crash at the end of the stage, losing the points he had earned from his tenth-place finish and ultimately the green jersey to Zabel,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=72}} who finished second in the stage.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=67}} Cipollini would again be successful on the following stage, winning the bunch sprint into [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]].{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=74}}\n\nAs the ferry reached French soil overnight into 14 July, the day of stage 3, all team vehicles were meticulously searched at customs.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=51}} During the day, Voet admitted to police that he had been following team orders, with Festina's team doctor [[Eric Rijkaert]] publicly denying he administered any banned substances. The next day, the team manager Bruno Roussel and Rijkaert were taken into police custody.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} Before that start of stage 5,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=64}} Jean-Marie Leblanc announced at a press conference that the professional licences held by Roussel and Rijkaert had been provisionally suspended by the UCI, and at that same time, Festina riders Richard Virenque, Laurent Brochard and Laurent Dufaux stated their intention to carry on racing.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} During stage 6, Roussel and Rijkaert confessed to systematic doping in the Festina squad. This led to the Tour organisation to expel the team ahead of the following stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|pp=246\u2013247}} Before the start of stage 7 Virenque, on behalf of Festina, held a private meeting with Leblanc to plead for the team to be allowed to continue, but to no avail.{{sfn|Fife|2000|p=202}}\n\nStage 7, the hilly and technical first long individual time trial, was won by Ullrich, 1:10 minutes ahead of {{ct|USP|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Tyler Hamilton]], with Julich in third a further eight seconds behind. O'Grady was fifteenth with a deficit of 3:17 minutes, and lost the yellow jersey to Ullrich, who was now 1:18 minutes in front of Hamburger and Julich on the same time in second and third respectively. Pantani finished thirty-third, 4:21 minutes slower than Ullrich, later saying that he had held himself back in anticipation of the upcoming Pyrenees.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=77\u201384}} Zanini regained the polka dot jersey.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Stage 8 was hilly and had very high temperatures; it ended with a group of six riders which fought out the victory 7:45 minutes ahead of the peloton. The sprint was won by [[Jacky Durand]] of {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}}, who had been in an escape group on every road stage so far. Four riders from the group gained enough time to move to the top of the general classification, with {{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Laurent Desbiens]] taking the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=85\u201391}} Temperatures increased to a high of {{convert|44|C}} during the following stage, which saw {{ct|RAB|1998|nolink=yes}} rider [[L\u00e9on van Bon]] win the final sprint which was contested between a four-man breakaway that was able to hold off the closing field by 12 seconds. Second place finisher [[Jens Voigt]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) collected enough mountains classification points from within the breakaway to take the polka dot jersey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tour de France, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 9 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage9.html|access-date=13 June 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=20 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701091323/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage9.html|archive-date=1 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Two-time stage winner Cipollini dropped out during this stage.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=116}}{{efn|Over the course of his career, [[Mario Cipollini]] had shown a tendency to avoid riding high mountain stages, which did not suit him, instead focusing on the flat stages in the first week of the race. In fact, he never finished a Tour de France in seven appearances, neither the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] in six attempts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abt |first1=Samuel |title=Cycling: Hardly a sprint, but Cipollini heads toward the end |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/09/sports/IHT-cycling-hardly-a-sprint-but-cipollini-heads-toward-the-end.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 September 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309122413/https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/09/sports/IHT-cycling-hardly-a-sprint-but-cipollini-heads-toward-the-end.html |archivedate=9 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===Pyrenees===\n[[File:Corniche Aubisque Soulor.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A green mountainside with a low-gradient road|Stage 10's descent on the eastern side of the [[Col d'Aubisque]] mountain pass (''pictured'') saw a total of 30 riders fall in the wet and foggy conditions.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=100}}]]\nStage 10 saw the race move into the high mountains, starting with the Pyrenees. On the way to [[Luchon]], four mountain passes had to be crossed: the [[Col d'Aubisque]], the [[Col du Tourmalet]], the [[Col d'Aspin]] and lastly the [[Col de Peyresourde]], followed by {{convert|15.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} of downhill to the finish line.<ref name=\"letour-10\">{{cite web|title=Casino gamble pays great dividends|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/10/|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=14 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212232716/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/10/|archivedate=12 December 2004}}</ref> A total of 30 riders fell on the wet and foggy descent of the Aubisque, including overall contenders Olano, Jalabert and Francesco Casagrande,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=99}} with the latter being one of six that retired from the race.<ref name=\"letour-10\" /> A three-rider breakaway of [[C\u00e9dric Vasseur]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) and {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}} teammates [[Rodolfo Massi]] and [[Alberto Elli]] had been formed by the foot of the Tourmalet. The pace set by {{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}} halfway up this climb split the peloton, with yellow jersey wearer Desbiens dropped. Massi moved clear from his fellow breakers on the steep section midway on {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}}-long last climb, and also at the same point after, a move by Ullrich formed a small group of elite riders which included pre-race favourites Pantani, Julich, Riis, Boogerd, Escart\u00edn and Jim\u00e9nez. Close to the top, Pantani launched a successful attack and summitted with an advantage of 42 seconds, but was unable to catch the soloing Massi on the descent,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=99\u2013106}} who took the stage victory as well as the lead of the mountains classification.<ref name=\"letour-10\" /> Pantani finished second, 33 seconds behind. Ullrich followed with the other favourites, a further 23 seconds back, to regain the yellow jersey, while Julich moved up to second overall.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=105\u2013106}}\n\nThe following stage 11 featured the first mountain-top finish of the 1998 Tour. As they did in that stage, the peloton agreed not to begin racing until after the first {{convert|45|km|mi|abbr=on}}, when they stopped to pay their respects at the memorial to [[Fabio Casartelli]] on the [[Col de Portet d'Aspet]], who crashed and died there on the 1995 Tour.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nicholl|first=Robin|title=Ullrich produces a tour de force|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/ullrich-produces-a-tour-de-force-1250966.html|access-date=14 June 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|date=16 July 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162041/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/ullrich-produces-a-tour-de-force-1250966.html|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Longmore|first=Andrew|title=Tour de France: From quiet American to big noise|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tour-de-france-from-quiet-american-to-big-noise-1102779.html|access-date=14 June 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|date=27 June 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162144/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tour-de-france-from-quiet-american-to-big-noise-1102779.html|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As the field headed the race at the bottom of the {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} climb to the finish at Plateau de Beille, Ullrich had a [[Flat tire|tyre puncture]]. Pantani was unaware of this and was about to attack, before being stopped by his teammate [[Roberto Conti]], as it breaches the [[Unspoken rule|unwritten rules]] of the peloton to attack a rider when they have mechanical issues. Having waited for Ullrich to regain contact, Pantani waited until {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish to attack, and after passing the sole breakaway rider, [[Roland Meier]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}), he took the stage win.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=108\u2013112}}{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=153}} Following Meier and a group of five led by Julich, Ullrich crossed the finish line in eighth place, 1:40 minutes down on Pantani. After the two stages in the Pyrenees, Ullrich led the general classification, 1:11 minutes ahead of Julich, with both Jalabert and Pantani 3:01 minutes down in third and fourth.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=112\u2013113}} Olano, a notable pre-race favourite, withdrew from the Tour halfway through the stage.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=108}}\n\n===Transition stages and rider unrest===\n[[File:Laurent JALABERT (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of wearing a pink jsery and headnad with \"ONCE\" insignia|[[Laurent Jalabert]] (''pictured in 1993'') of the {{ct|ONC|1998}} team was an influential figure in both of the Tour's rider [[Sit-in|sit-down]] protests during stages 12 and 17.]]\nAfter the rest day, stage 12 followed a flat course between [[Tarascon-sur-Ari\u00e8ge]] and [[Cap d'Agde]]. Anger had grown amongst the riders amid the treatment of them by the police and the press in light of the evolving Festina affair. They were also unhappy with the looming expulsion of the TVM team, against which the police had renewed their investigation which was started in March, as well as journalists going through waste containers at team hotels, searching for evidence of performance-enhancing drugs. Some riders also spoke out against the announcement by the UCI to move forward the introduction of new health tests.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=138}} As the riders lined up with their bikes at the start of the stage, Jalabert broadcast a statement on their behalf on the race's official station, Radio Tour, saying \"We are fed up with being treated like cattle. So we are going to behave like cattle.\"{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=118}}\n\nFollowing this, the majority of the riders sat down in the road and entered into a strike.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=118}} The biggest influence during the strike was attributed to Jalabert, Blijlevens, [[Max Sciandri]] ({{ct|FDJ|1998|nolink=yes}}), and [[Prudencio Indur\u00e1in]] ({{ct|VIT|1998|nolink=yes}}) as well as ONCE's team manager [[Manolo Saiz]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=139\u2013140}} Leblanc negotiated with all of the team managers and they voted 14\u20136 in agreement to begin the stage. The peloton and vehicles slowly set off, but a Jalabert-led group of about 40 refused. They eventually relented and caught up to the rest {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} ahead, and the race started, exactly two hours after the scheduled time. Jalabert then went on the attack over a short climb with his brother [[Nicolas Jalabert|Nicolas]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}) and [[Bart Voskamp]] (TVM), who built up a lead of over five minutes. Team Telekom gave chase at a high pace, temporarily putting Pantani into difficulty as crosswinds created echelons in the peloton.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=141\u2013143}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=119\u2013121}} The trio of escapees were eventually brought back. Steels took his second stage win of the Tour in a bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=119\u2013122}} The shortened stage was run at an average speed of {{convert|48.764|kph|mph|abbr=on}}, breaking the Tour record of the fastest ever stage over {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}},{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=122}} as well as the third-fastest of any distance stage in Tour history.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=143}}\n\nStage 13 saw a breakaway by six riders, among them [[Daniele Nardello]] and [[Andrea Tafi (cyclist)|Andrea Tafi]], both of Team {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}}. They worked together at the finish to ensure Nardello took Mapei's fourth stage win. At the only classified climb of the day, [[Luc Leblanc]] ({{ct|POL|1998|nolink=yes}}) put in an attack, but was brought back by Riis.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=152}} The following day's stage brought the Tour to [[Grenoble]] at the foot of the Alps. The stage was won by O'Grady, again from a breakaway.<ref name=\"cn-14\">{{cite news|title=Tour de France, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 14 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage14.html|access-date=17 June 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=26 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322165454/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage14.html|archive-date=22 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the press conference after, Ullrich was asked whether his team would be capable of supporting him in the Alps and, after initially appearing upbeat, he ended his response with: \"Even if I don't have the yellow jersey in Paris, I want to give my compliments to the team\".{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=134\u2013135}} Pantani, who still stood at fourth overall, was quoted saying: \"My main goal now is to win in Les Deux-Alpes.\"<ref name=\"cn-14\" />\n\n===Alps and second strike===\n[[File:Pantani Bike 1998 TdF.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A turquoise and yellow Bianchi bicycle hung up at a cycle show stand|One of the [[racing bicycle]]s that was used by [[Marco Pantani]] during the Tour's mountain stages]]\nStage 15 was the first of three Alpine stages. After a warm start in Grenoble, the weather soon deteriorated, with cold temperatures, rain and fog impeding the riders. The route contained four classified climbs, including the ''hors categorie'' [[Col de la Croix de Fer]] and Col du Galibier, and ending with a summit finish at Les Deux Alpes.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=164}} On the Croix de Fer, Massi bridged over to a breakaway group and scored maximum points for the mountains classification, a feat he repeated on the second climb of the day, the [[Col du T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe]]. By this point, the lead group contained only Massi, [[Christophe Rinero]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}) and [[Marcos-Antonio Serrano]] ({{ct|KEL|1998|nolink=yes}}). Behind them in the group of the main favourites, the high climbing tempo put Jalabert into difficulty, which ultimately saw him drop far down the general classification by the end of the stage.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=165}} After the short descent of the T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe, the race reached the Galibier, where Riis cracked following his work reeling back attackers, leaving Ullrich without a teammate.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=166}} With {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} remaining to the summit of the Galibier, Pantani made the decisive move of the race, attacking from the group of favourites.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=141}} By the summit of the climb, Pantani had passed all the breakaway riders and was out in front alone, leading by ten seconds. Ullrich reached the top 2:41 minutes behind Pantani. Crucially, unlike Pantani, he did not wear a raincoat during the descent. He subsequently suffered from the cold and [[hyperglycemia]] for the rest of the stage.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|pages=124\u2013126}} The breakaway caught up to Pantani on the descent of the Galibier, forming a group of strong climbers. Before the final climb to Les Deux Alpes, Ullrich had a tyre puncture and was distanced by the group of chasers. On the climb, Pantani soon moved clear of his group and took the stage victory, almost two minutes ahead of Massi in second place. Ullrich finished with teammates [[Udo B\u00f6lts]] and Riis 8:57 minutes after Pantani, who took over the yellow jersey. He led Julich by 3:53 minutes, with Escart\u00edn in third place in the general classification, ahead of Ullrich.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=142\u2013146}}\n\nBefore the following stage to [[Albertville]], speculation spread that Ullrich would abandon the race.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=187}} Pantani's Mercatone Uno team coped well in defending his yellow over the four lesser categorised climbs, until the race reached the ''hors categorie'' final climb, the [[Col de la Madeleine]], when Ullrich attacked, with only Pantani able to follow. Ullrich led the duo up the rest of the climb as they passed the breakaway riders and increased their advantage over the chasing Julich, who was accompanied by two teammates. The pair held their lead of around two minutes along the final {{convert|17|km|mi|abbr=on}} of flat, where at the finish, Ullrich outsprinted Pantani to the stage win. Pantani now led Julich by 5:42 minutes, with Ullrich third, just over six minutes behind.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=147\u2013152}}\n\nAnother police raid on the TVM team and news about alleged mistreatment of the Festina riders while in custody led to another riders' strike on stage 17. After a brief stop of two minutes at the start, the riders rode slowly to the first intermediate sprint of the day, where they climbed off their bikes and sat on the road. Jalabert climbed into his team car and retired from the race. Meanwhile, Jean-Marie Leblanc negotiated with the riders and collected guarantees from a civil servant from the [[Ministry of the Interior (France)|French Ministry of the Interior]], who was visiting the Tour as a guest, that police treatment of the riders would improve. Nevertheless, the entire ONCE team followed their leader Jalabert and abandoned. As the riders slowly got moving again, they ripped off their race numbers as a further sign of protest. Luc Leblanc retired later in the stage. At the feed zone, the Banesto squad joined their fellow Spanish-based ONCE team in quitting, as well as the Italian-based Riso Scotti team. The field reached the finishing town, [[Aix-les-Bains]], two hours behind schedule. The TVM team was allowed to cross the line first as a sign of solidarity; while the stage was annulled and no results counted. Overnight, two more Spanish-based teams, Kelme and Vitalicio Seguros, also decided not to carry on in the Tour. This caused the retirement of the fourth rider overall, Escart\u00edn of Kelme.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=202\u2013223}}\n\n===Conclusion===\n[[File:Marco Pantani.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Marco Pantani wearing a bandana and glasses on his head|[[Marco Pantani]] (''pictured in 1997'') was the overall winner of the Tour, completing the [[Giro-Tour double]], as he had also won the [[1998 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] earlier in the season.]]\nBefore stage 18 into [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] in Switzerland, police held Massi, who was still the leader in the mountains classification, for questioning after [[corticoid]]s were allegedly found in his room during a search of the Casino team hotel.{{efn|Massi was later cleared of all charges.<ref>{{cite news |title='Festina Affair': A timeline |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/988530.stm |accessdate=30 October 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 October 2000}}</ref>}} He was therefore unable to start the stage,<ref name=\"wp-troubled\">{{cite news |last1=Thomazeau |first1=Francois |title=Troubled Tour Resumes; Steels Wins 18th Stage |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/tour31.htm |url-access=limited |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=30 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604145145/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/tour31.htm|archive-date=4 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the lead of the mountains classification was passed to the second placed rider, Rinero.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Victory went to Steels, who outsprinted Zabel and O'Grady at the finish.<ref name=\"wp-troubled\"  /> The remaining five riders from TVM exited the race on Swiss soil before the start of the following day. Stage 19 went back into France and saw a breakaway of 13 riders. Four riders broke away from the lead group to contest the stage win between them, with [[Magnus B\u00e4ckstedt]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) coming out on top.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Backstedt's Late Surge Gives Him Slim Victory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/01/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-backstedt-s-late-surge-gives-him-slim-victory.html |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1 August 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527073216/http://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/01/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-backstedt-s-late-surge-gives-him-slim-victory.html |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe penultimate stage saw the last individual time trial of the race to [[Le Creusot]]. Ullrich won the stage, 1:01 minutes ahead of Julich, to move into second place overall. Pantani finished the stage third, 2:35 minutes behind Ullrich, effectively sealing his victory in the general classification.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=174\u2013175}} The final stage on the Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es in Paris was won by Steels from a bunch sprint, while Pantani finished safely in the peloton to secure the Tour win.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=177}} Ullrich ended the Tour in second place, with a deficit of 3:21 minutes, with Julich a further 47 seconds behind in third.<ref name=\"letour-21-gc\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall standings|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/itg.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221194735/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/itg.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Pantani was greeted on the podium by [[Felice Gimondi]], who had been invited by Jean-Marie Leblanc to present to the crowd the first Italian winner since his own victory in [[1965 Tour de France|1965]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westemeyer |first1=Susan |title=Gimondi on Pantani film and cyclist |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/gimondi-on-pantani-film-and-cyclist/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=5 February 2007}}</ref> Zabel won his third consecutive points classification with a total of 327, 97 ahead of O'Grady in second.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=119}}<ref name=\"letour-21-points\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall sprinters|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/ipg.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221164955/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/ipg.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Although Pantani won two high mountain stages, the mountains classification was won by a more consistent Rinero, whose total of 200 points was 25 more than that of second-placed Pantani.<ref name=\"letour-21-mountains\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall climbers|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/img.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221125924/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/img.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Due to the high number of abandons because of the Festina affair, only 96 riders reached the finish in Paris.<ref name=\"letour-21-gc\" /> Only Team Telekom and U.S. Postal Service ended the Tour with all nine riders still racing.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=39}}\n\n===Doping===\n{{main|Doping at the 1998 Tour de France}}\nThe prevalence of EPO in the cycling peloton had been a topic of debate since the early 1990s.{{sfn|Woodland|2003|p=142}} First news stories about the drug appeared in 1994.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=106}} The UCI gave the task of developing a test for EPO to [[Francesco Conconi]], a professor at the [[University of Ferrara]], Italy, and a member of the UCI Medical Commission. In June 1996, Conconi, seemingly unable to find a definite test for the substance,{{efn|Around the year 2000, investigations in Italy revealed that Conconi had used the money given to him by the UCI to provide EPO to professional cyclists.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=109}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Capodacqua |first1=Eugenio |title=Ecco il doping di Conconi |trans-title=Here is the doping of Conconi|url=https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/pantapro/capo/capo.html |accessdate=30 October 2019 |work=[[la Repubblica]] |date=27 October 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030105104/https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/pantapro/capo/capo.html |archivedate=30 October 2019 |language=Italian}}</ref> A promising test for EPO by Canadian scientist Guy Brisson, who conducted a trial run during the [[1996 Tour de Suisse]] and found indications of EPO abuse in all tested 77 riders, was not followed up by the UCI, due to fear that the test would not \"stand up to legal challenges\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=112\u2013113}}}} proposed to the UCI to introduce a test for an athlete's [[hematocrit]] level instead, meaning to test the amount of [[Red blood cell|red cells]] in the blood.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=109}} During the UCI's meeting in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, on 24 January 1997, the procedure, labelled as a \"health test\", limiting the allowed hematocrit level to 50 per cent, was introduced.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Daniel T. |last2=Ashenden |first2=Michael |last3=Parisotto |first3=Robin |last4=Pyne |first4=David |last5=Hahn |first5=Allan G. |title=Blood Testing for Professional Cyclists: What's a fair hematocrit limit? |url=http://www.sportsci.org/news/news9703/AISblood.html |website=sportsci.org |publisher=Sportscience News |accessdate=16 August 2019 |date=1997}}</ref> Failing to test below the given value resulted in the rider being barred from competing for a two-week period. However, as cycling journalist [[Alasdair Fotheringham]] described it, \"the 50 per cent threshold became a target to aim for\" instead of a reliable deterrent to using EPO.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=107}}\n\nThe doping scandal that occurred throughout the Tour became known as the [[Festina affair]],<ref name=\"cn_1998\">{{cite web |last1=Whittle |first1=Jeremy |title=The 1998 Tour de France: Police raids, arrests, protests... and a bike race |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/the-1998-tour-de-france-police-raids-arrests-protests-and-a-bike-race/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=25 June 2019 |date=3 March 2017}}</ref> starting with the arrest of Voet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tour rocked by drugs arrest |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1998/07/98/tour_de_france/130515.stm |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=11 July 1998}}</ref> Initially the doping suspicion only surrounded the Festina and TVM teams, but later investigations and retrospective tests revealed the doping abuse was far more widespread. Therefore, this edition of the Tour also became nicknamed by many media sources as the \"Tour de Farce\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=Dust jacket}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Fotheringham|first=William|author-link=William Fotheringham|title=Scandal revives doping fears|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/jan/28/cycling.cycling|access-date=18 June 2019|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|date=28 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618164423/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/jan/28/cycling.cycling|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ausblenden und Gesundbeten |trans-title=Suppressing and Healing Through Faith |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7941085.html |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |issue=31/1998 |page=104 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222014555/http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7941085.html |archive-date=22 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> or \"Tour du Dopage\" (Tour of Doping).<ref>{{cite news |title=De positieve renners van de Tour du dopage |trans-title=The positive riders of the Tour du Dopage |url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/de-positieve-renners-van-de-tour-du-dopage~q0570442/ |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[de Volkskrant]] |date=24 July 2013 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Radsport: TVM-Aff\u00e4re 1998: Blijlevens und Voskamp gestehen Epo-Doping | trans-title=TVM affair: Blijlevens and Voskamp admit to EPO doping| url=https://www.focus.de/sport/radsport/radsport-tvm-affaere-1998-blijlevens-und-voskamp-gestehen-epo-doping_id_3983157.html |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] |agency=[[Sport-Informations-Dienst]] |date=11 July 2014 |language=German}}</ref>{{sfn|Waddington|2001|p=159}} Following Festina's expulsion from the race, the police's investigation against the TVM team was made public by ''[[Le Parisien]]'' and the case reopened.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=96}}\n\nThe riders in the Tour reacted differently to the developing scandal. [[Rolf Aldag]] ({{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}}) says he flushed his doping products down the toilet before the race began in Dublin.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=1}} His teammate Bjarne Riis stated in his autobiography that he disposed of his vials of EPO in the toilet after stage 3.{{sfn|Riis|Pedersen|2012|p=171}} Likewise, the U.S. Postal team flushed their drugs down the toilet following Voet's arrest, according to Tyler Hamilton.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=92}} According to J\u00f6rg Jaksche, the Polti squad hid their supply of EPO in a vacuum cleaner on the team bus, while he also stated his belief that most Italian teams kept their drugs during the race as well. [[Philippe Gaumont]] claimed in his autobiography that the Cofidis team were told by the team management to destroy their substances on the day that the Festina team was expelled, with the riders subsequently going into a forest and disposing of the products.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=60\u201361}} Julich meanwhile states that he quit doping altogether during the 1998 Tour.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=279}}\n\nAfter their arrests, Voet, Roussel, and Rijckaert gave confessions of the doping practices at Festina to the police. Roussel stated that one per cent of the team's budget (around \u20ac40,000) was used to pay for EPO and [[human growth hormone]]s.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=71}} The riders on Festina were placed under custody and brought into individual prison cells, and allegedly subjected to [[Body cavity search|cavity search]]es. On 24 July, four Festina riders had confessed to taking performance-enhancing drugs, with the first being Alex Z\u00fclle. The only riders to deny the allegations were Virenque and [[Neil Stephens]].{{efn|Stephens maintains that he took EPO unknowingly, having thought it to be vitamin supplements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aubrey |first1=Jane |title=Orica-GreenEdge owner unaware of Stephens' past admissions |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/orica-greenedge-owner-unaware-of-stephens-past-admissions/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=16 August 2019 |date=12 December 2012}}</ref>}}{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=135\u2013138}} Examinations carried out on the nine Festina riders on 23 July, with the results being published on 28 November, revealing that eight riders took EPO and four amphetamines. Virenque was the only rider not to test positive in these tests.<ref name=\"cn_history\">{{cite web |title=News for October 25, 2000 |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/2000/oct00/oct25news.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=25 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July, the Tour's rest day, TVM's manager Cees Priem and team doctor Andrei Mikhailov were also arrested by the police.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=135}} At the beginning of August, team ''soigneur'' Johannes Moors was taken into custody as well.<ref name=\"cn_4august98\">{{cite web |title=News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> Priem and Moors were released on 10 August.<ref name=cn_11august>{{cite web |title=News for August 11, 1998: Drugs Scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug11.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=11 August 1998}}</ref>  The TVM riders were also questioned by the police on 4 August and held for about 12 hours, before they were released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Edition News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4a.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> However, no banned substances were found during the raid at TVM's team hotel during the Tour.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 8, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug8.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=8 August 1998}}</ref> At ONCE and BigMat, police did find performance-enhancing drugs during their raids. ONCE maintained that the substances were for medical use of the team staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> Police called in twelve riders from BigMat for questioning along with the ''[[directeur sportif]]'' and some ''soigneurs'' a week after the end of the Tour because of \"330 bottles and ampoules of drugs\" found in the team's truck.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 15, 1998: Drugs Update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug15.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=15 August 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe legal investigation about doping at the 1998 Tour was given to judge Patrick Keil shortly after the race concluded. He handed in his 5539-page report on the matter at the beginning of July 1999, which laid the groundwork for subsequent legal proceedings against team staff and riders.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for July 2, 1999 |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1999/jul99/jul2.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=2 July 1999}}</ref> Virenque confessed during a court hearing concerning the Festina affair, on 24 October 2000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hamoir |first1=Oliver |title=Virenque: 'I took drugs, I had no choice' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/virenque-i-took-drugs-i-had-no-choice-637089.html |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=25 October 2000}}</ref> Virenque received a nine-month racing ban and a suspended prison sentence.{{efn|Virenque appealed the decision at the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland. The Court considered to turn his ban into a suspended sentence. They eventually upheld the verdict, but brought its start date forward, meaning Virenque was able to return to competition on 14 August 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for March 13, 2001: Virenque's suspension brought forward |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/2001/mar01/mar13news.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=13 March 2001}}</ref>}} Voet was sentenced to a suspended ten months in prison and a fine of 3,000 franc. Roussell received a one-year suspended sentence and a 50,000 franc fine. Lesser verdicts were handed out to \"two masseurs, the team's logistics manager, the team doctor at the Spanish ONCE team, Nicolas Terrados, and two pharmacists\".<ref name=\"guardian_verdict\">{{cite news |last1=Fotheringham |first1=William |author-link=William Fotheringham |title=Festina trial ends with fines and a warning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,415051,00.html |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 December 2000}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Tour, 108 tests for performance-enhancing drugs were carried out by France's main anti-doping laboratory in [[Ch\u00e2tenay-Malabry]]. All of them were negative.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=101}}{{sfn|Waddington|Smith|2009|p=148}} In 2004, 60 remaining anti-doping samples given by riders during the 1998 Tour were tested retrospectively for recombinant EPO by using three recently developed detection methods. The results of these tests were published to have returned 44 positives and 9 negatives, with the remaining 7 samples not returning any result due to sample degradation. At first, the rider names with a positive sample were not made public, as it had only been conducted as scientific research.<ref name=\"Derni\u00e8re Heure\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dhnet.be/sports/tourdefrance/1998-plane-sur-le-centieme-tour-de-france-51cbd867357030bb907bbd54|title=1998 plane sur le centi\u00e8me Tour de France|trans-title=1998 flat on the hundredth Tour de France|language=French|work=[[La Derni\u00e8re Heure]]|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630073932/http://www.dhnet.be/sports/tourdefrance/1998-plane-sur-le-centieme-tour-de-france-51cbd867357030bb907bbd54|archive-date=30 June 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, the anti-doping committee of the [[French Senate]] decided it would benefit the current doping fight to shed full light on the past, and so decided&nbsp;\u2013 as part of their \"Commission of Inquiry into the effectiveness of the fight against doping\" report&nbsp;\u2013 to publish all sample IDs along with the result of the retrospective test. This publication revealed, that the 9 negative samples belonged to 5 riders (of whom two nevertheless had confessed using EPO in that Tour), while the 44 positive samples belonged to 33 riders&nbsp;\u2013 including race winner Pantani, Ullrich, Julich, and Zabel.<ref name=\"Positive EPO cases\">{{cite web|title=Cipollini, Livingston among 1998 Tour riders positive for EPO|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2013/07/news/pantini-ullrich-among-1998-tour-riders-positive-for-epo_296750|work=[[VeloNews]]|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728091214/http://velonews.competitor.com/2013/07/news/pantini-ullrich-among-1998-tour-riders-positive-for-epo_296750|archive-date=28 July 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"44 Positive EPO Samples\">{{cite web|title=Rapport Fait au nom de la commission d\u2019enqu\u00eate sur l\u2019efficacit\u00e9 de la lutte contre le dopage (Annexe 6: R\u00e9sultats test EPO Tour De France 1998 et 1999)|trans-title=Report Made on behalf of the commission of inquiry into the effectiveness of the fight against doping (Appendix 6: EPO test results Tour de France 1998 and 1999)|url=http://www.senat.fr/rap/r12-782-2/r12-782-21.pdf|format=PDF|language=French|work=N\u00b0 782, S\u00e9nat Session Extraordinaire de 2012\u20132013|publisher=French Senate|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806234902/http://www.senat.fr/rap/r12-782-2/r12-782-21.pdf|archive-date=6 August 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Julich had already admitted using EPO from August 1996 to July 1998 one year prior to this publication.<ref name=\"Julich confession\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/exclusive-bobby-julich-doping-confession|title=Exclusive: Bobby Julich doping confession|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=25 October 2012|accessdate=25 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025181017/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/exclusive-bobby-julich-doping-confession|archive-date=25 October 2012|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n[[File:Erik ZABEL (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Erik Zabel wearing a pink jersey and cap|[[Erik Zabel]] ({{ct|TEL|1998}}, ''pictured in 2002'') won the [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]] for the third time in a row.]]\nThere were several classifications in the 1998 Tour de France.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013455}} The most important was the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} Jan Ullrich wore the yellow jersey in the prologue as the winner of the previous edition.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=27}} Time bonuses were given during the first half of the Tour to the first three finishers on each stage, excluding mountain stages and time trials. The winner received a 20-second bonus, the second finisher 12 seconds and the third rider 8 seconds.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pages=128\u2013129}} During the first half of the race, intermediate sprints also had time bonuses, with bonuses of 6, 4, and 2 seconds given to the first three riders to cross the line.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=183}}\n\nAdditionally, there was a [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]], in which cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=453\u2013454}} In flat stages, the first 25 finishers received points, 35 for the stage winner down to 1 point for 25th place. In medium mountain stages, the top-20 finishers received points, with 25 points for the stage winner down to 1 point. In mountain stages, the first 15 finishers received points, with 20 points given to the stage winner. In time trials, 15 points were given to the winner, down to 1 point for the tenth-placed finisher.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=154}} Points could also be won during intermediate sprints along the race route, with 6, 4, and 2 points for the first three riders across the line respectively.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=182}} The cyclist with the most points led the classification, and was identified by a green jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=453\u2013454}}\n\nThere was also a [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]]. Most stages of the race included one or more categorised climbs, in which points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit first. The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second- or first-category and ''hors cat\u00e9gorie'', with the more difficult climbs rated lower.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} The first rider to cross the summit of an ''hors cat\u00e9gorie'' climb was given 40 points (down to 1 point for the 15th rider). Twelve riders received points for first category climbs, with 30 for the first rider to reach the summit. Second-, third- and fourth-category climbs gave 20, 10 and 5 points to the first rider respectively.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=164}} The cyclist with the most points led the classification, wearing a white jersey with red polka dots.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}\n\nThe [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|young rider classification]], which was not marked by a jersey, was decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders under 26 years were eligible.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=454\u2013455}} This meant that in order to compete in the classification, a rider had to be born after 1 January 1973. 34 out of the 189 starters were eligible.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pages=174\u2013175}} Jan Ullrich won the classification for the third time in a row.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=176}}\n\nFor the [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]], the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}}\n\nIn addition, there was a [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|combativity award]] given after each mass-start stage to the cyclist considered the most combative. The winner of the award wore a red number bib during the next stage, this feature was introduced for the first time in 1998. The decision was made by a jury composed of journalists who gave points. The cyclist with the most points from votes in all stages led the combativity classification.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pp=211\u2013216}}{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}} Jacky Durand won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=89}} The [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col du Galibier on stage 15. The winner of the prize was Marco Pantani.<ref name=\"cn-15\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Leaders overview|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216224428/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1998|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1998|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1998|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302052644/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1998|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|link=General classification in the Tour de France|alt=A yellow jersey.]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Points classification in the Tour de France|Points classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey green.svg|25px|link=Points classification in the Tour de France|alt=A green jersey]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|25px|link=Mountains classification in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with red polka dots.]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]]{{efn|A white jersey was not awarded to the leader of the young rider classification between [[1989 Tour de France|1989]] and [[1999 Tour de France|1999]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=454\u2013455}}}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]<!-- no yellow number bib given before 2006 -->\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:22%;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|Combativity]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" | [[File:Jersey red number.svg|20px|link=Combativity award in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with a red number bib.]] Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" | Classification\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Prologue|P]]\n| [[Chris Boardman]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Chris Boardman]]\n| style=\"background:#9CE97B;\" | [[Chris Boardman]]\n| ''no award''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Jan Ullrich]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{ct|FES|1998}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''no award''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Tom Steels]]\n| style=\"background:#9CE97B;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Tom Steels]]\n| style=\"background:#FFA8A4;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stefano Zanini]]\n| style=\"background:#E4B3AB;\" | [[Jacky Durand]]\n| rowspan=\"21\" | [[Jacky Durand]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n|