irst2=James|title=In Pursuit of the Yellow Jersey: Bicycle Racing in the Year of the Tortured Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_UADAAAACAAJ|date=1999|publisher=Cycle Publishing|location=San Francisco, CA|isbn=978-1-892495-16-7}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tour de France 1998|1998 Tour de France}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981202155449/http://www.letour.fr/98us/ |date=2 December 1998 |title=Official website }}{{cbignore}}\n* [http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/tdf98.html 1998 Tour de France] at [[Cyclingnews.com]]\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1998 Tour de France|P|11|12|21}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1998 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1998 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1998 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1998 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1998 in Swiss sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Cycle racing in Ireland]]\n[[Category:1998 in Irish sport]]\n[[Category:July 1998 sports events in Europe|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:August 1998 sports events in Europe|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "Zwerg Nase", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly stages in Ireland:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Lake Sterzh", "text_new": "{{Infobox lake\n | name = Lake Sterzh\n | image = Lake sterzh1.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Tver Oblast]] \n | coords = {{coord|57|10|7|N|32|36|19|E|region:RU_source:ruwiki_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n | type = \n | inflow = [[Volga River|Volga]]\n | outflow = [[Volga River|Volga]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = Russia\n | length = {{convert|12|km|mi}}\n | width = {{convert|1500|m|ft}}\n | area = {{convert|17.9|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n | depth = {{convert|5|m|ft}}\n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Sterzh''' (\u0421\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0436) is the third largest among the [[Valdai Lakes]] in [[Tver Oblast]] of [[Russia]]. It is the first [[lake]] through which the [[Volga]] flows. The lake's length is {{convert|12|km|mi}}, its width is up to {{convert|1500|m|ft}}, and the average depth is {{convert|5|m|ft}}. The area of the lake is {{convert|17.9|km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"register\">{{GVR|174253}}</ref> The lake gives its name to the [[Sterzh Cross]].\n\nLake Sterzh is oriented north to south, with one bay stretching to the east. The Volga flows in the northern part of the lake. In the south, Lake Sterzh continues as [[Lake Vselug]]. Together with Lake Vselug, [[Lake Peno]], and [[Lake Volgo]] it forms [[Upper Volga Reservoir]]. The lake is shared between [[Ostashkovsky District|Ostashkovsky]] (north) and [[Penovsky District|Penovsky]] (south) Districts of Tver Oblast.\n\nThe [[drainage basin]] of Lake Sterzh includes the northern part of Ostashkovsky District and minor areas in the northeast of Penovsky District.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Tver Oblast|Sterzh]]\n[[Category:Volga basin|LSterzh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n | name = Lake Sterzh\n | image = Lake sterzh1.jpg\n | caption = \n | image_bathymetry = \n | caption_bathymetry = \n | location = [[Tver Oblast]] \n | coords = {{coord|57|10|7|N|32|36|19|E|region:RU_source:ruwiki_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n | type = \n | inflow = [[Volga River|Volga]]\n | outflow = [[Volga River|Volga]]\n | catchment = \n | basin_countries = Russia\n | length = {{convert|12|km|mi}}\n | width = {{convert|1500|m|ft}}\n | area = {{convert|17.9|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"register\"/>\n | depth = {{convert|5|m|ft}}\n | max-depth = \n | volume = \n | residence_time = \n | shore = \n | elevation = \n | islands = \n | cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Sterzh''' (\u0421\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0436) is the third largest among the [[Valdai Lakes]] in [[Tver Oblast]] of [[Russia]]. It is the first [[lake]] through which the [[Volga]] flows. The lake's length is {{convert|12|km|mi}}, its width is up to {{convert|1500|m|ft}}, and the average depth is {{convert|5|m|ft}}. The area of the lake is {{convert|17.9|km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"register\">{{GVR|174253}}</ref> The lake gives its name to the [[Sterzh Cross]].\n\nLake Sterzh is oriented north to south, with one bay stretching to the east. The Volga flows in the northern part of the lake. In the south, Lake Sterzh continues as [[Lake Vselug]]. Together with Lake Vselug, [[Lake Peno]], and [[Lake Volgo]] it forms [[Upper Volga Reservoir]]. The lake is shared between [[Ostashkovsky District|Ostashkovsky]] (north) and [[Penovsky District|Penovsky]] (south) Districts of Tver Oblast.\n\nThe [[drainage basin]] of Lake Sterzh includes the northern part of Ostashkovsky District and minor areas in the northeast of Penovsky District.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Tver Oblast|Sterzh]]\n[[Category:Volga River]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Sterzh"}
{"title_page": "Scot Weir", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Scot Weir\n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| caption = Benedikt \n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[tenor]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* [[Musiktheater im Revier]]\n* [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]]\n* [[Zurich University of the Arts]]\n}}\n| awards = \n| website =     \n}}\n'''Scot Weir''' (born 1956) is an American [[lyric tenor]] in opera and concert, and an academic teacher who made a career in Europe. He has been professor of voice at the [[Zurich University of the Arts]].\n\n== Life ==\nWeir moved to Europe in 1980, where he first worked at the [[Musiktheater im Revier]] in Gelsenkirchen and the [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]]. He also appeared at the [[Vienna State Opera]], the [[Salzburg Festival]], to Amsterdam, Paris and Torino.\n\nHe has been active in concert, known for [[lied]]er singing and for interpreting music by [[johann Sebastian Bach]]. He worked with conductors such as [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Charles Dutoit]], [[Philippe Herreweghe]], [[Charles Mackerras]], [[Roger Norrington]], [[Helmuth Rilling]] and [[Peter Schreier]].<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\" />\n\nWeir has been professor of voice and chamber music at the [[Zurich University of the Arts]].<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\" />\n\n== Recordings ==\nWeir's recordings include sacred muic by Schubert, with the [[Mass No. 6 (Schubert)|Mass No. 6]]. A reviewer noted his !sensitivity and impressive breath control\".<ref name=\"Wigmore\" /> In 2000, he took part in a recording of Haydn's opera ''[[Armida (Haydn)|Armida]]'', with the [[Concentus Musicus Wien]] conducted by [[Nikolaus Harnoncourt]], alongside [[Cecilia Bartoli]] and [[Christoph Pr\u00e9gardien]].<ref name=\"Hengelbrock\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Hengelbrock\">{{cite web\n| last = Hengelbrock\n| first = Matthias\n| url = http://www.klassik-heute.com/4daction/www_medien_einzeln?id=10706&Inter13679\n| title = Haydn: Armida\n| website = klassik-heute.com\n| date = 1 December 2000\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 21 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wigmore\">{{cite journal\n| last = Wigmore\n| first = Richard\n| url = https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/schubert-mass-d950-offertorium-d963-tantum-ergo-d962\n| title = Schubert Mass, D950; Offertorium, D963; Tantum ergo, D962\n|journal = [[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]\n| date = October 1998\n| accessdate = 21 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.zhdk.ch/en/person/148684\n| title = Prof. Dr. h.c. mult Scot Weir / Lehrt Gesang (Hauptfach) und Kammermusik im Profil Klassik\n| website = [[Z]]\n| date = 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 21 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!--* {{DNB portal|1067162100}}\n* {{official|http://www.kristjansson-tenor.com/}}-->\n* {{Allmusic|id=mn0002057249}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* [https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Weir-Scot.htm Scot Weir (Tenor)] Bach Cantatas Website\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, Scot}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American operatic tenors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Scot Weir\n| image = \n| image_upright = \n| caption = Benedikt \n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[tenor]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* [[Musiktheater im Revier]]\n* [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]]\n* [[Zurich University of the Arts]]\n}}\n| awards = \n| website =     \n}}\n'''Scot Weir''' (born 1956) is an American [[lyric tenor]] in opera and concert, and an academic teacher who made a career in Europe. He has been professor of voice at the [[Zurich University of the Arts]].\n\n== Life ==\nWeir was born in [[H\u00fasav\u00edk]]. He studied first with his . He moved to Europe in 1980, where he first worked at the [[Musiktheater im Revier]] in Gelsenkirchen and the [[Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden]]. He also appeared at the [[Vienna State Opera]], the [[Salzburg Festival]], to Amsterdam, Paris and Torino.\n\nHe has been active in concert, known for [[lied]]er singing and for interpreting music by [[johann Sebastian Bach]]. He worked with conductors such as [[Claudio Abbado]], [[Charles Dutoit]], [[Philippe Herreweghe]], [[Charles Mackerras]], [[Roger Norrington]], [[Helmuth Rilling]] and [[Peter Schreier]].<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\" />\n\nWeir has been professor of voice and chamber music at the [[Zurich University of the Arts]].<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\" />\n\n== Recordings ==\nWeir's recordings include sacred muic by Schubert, with the [[Mass No. 6 (Schubert)|Mass No. 6]]. A reviewer noted his !sensitivity and impressive breath control\".<ref name=\"Wigmore\" /> In 2000, he took part in a recording of Haydn's opera ''[[Armida (Haydn)|Armida]]'', with the [[Concentus Musicus Wien]] conducted by [[Nikolaus Harnoncourt]], alongside [[Cecilia Bartoli]] and [[Christoph Pr\u00e9gardien]].<ref name=\"Hengelbrock\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Hengelbrock\">{{cite web\n| last = Hengelbrock\n| first = Matthias\n| url = http://www.klassik-heute.com/4daction/www_medien_einzeln?id=10706&Inter13679\n| title = Haydn: Armida\n| website = klassik-heute.com\n| date = 1 December 2000\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 21 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wigmore\">{{cite journal\n| last = Wigmore\n| first = Richard\n| url = https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/schubert-mass-d950-offertorium-d963-tantum-ergo-d962\n| title = Schubert Mass, D950; Offertorium, D963; Tantum ergo, D962\n|journal = [[Gramophone (magazine)|Gramophone]]\n| date = October 1998\n| accessdate = 21 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Z\u00fcrich\">{{cite web\n| url = http